<HEADLINE> Patten's Final Policy Address Disappointing: Commentary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Governor Chris
Patten issued his final policy address on Wednesday, demonstrating
once again his opposition to the establishment of the provisional
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Soon after taking office in 1992, Chris Patten introduced his
"political reform" and damaged the "through-train" arrangements,
stirring up a dispute between China and Britain.
</P>
<P>
After four years he not only failed to examine his mistakes,
but tried to seek every possible means to defend himself, saying
that "political reform" has nothing to do with any issues that
contravene the "Joint Declaration" or the "Basic Law", regardless
of facts.
</P>
<P>
In the policy address Patten again hurled attacks upon the
provisional legislature, and pledged to draw a demarcation line
with it.
</P>
<P>
As for the reason why he is so hostile to the provisional
legislature, one newspaper pointed out in its editorial that the
decision to establish a provisional legislature smashed his
"political reform" as well as his fond dream to extend the
three-tier political framework designed by himself beyond 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the final address, Patten said that he would give all-out
support to the chief executive-designate upon the establishment of
the Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, and he also claimed that he would offer the "best
cooperation and assistance".
</P>
<P>
But when the Preparatory Committee submitted ten requirements
to seek cooperation from the British Hong Kong government, Patten
abandoned his commitment.
</P>
<P>
Britain's colonial rule over Hong Kong will terminate on June
30. 1997. The question of how Hong Kong is administered from July
1st 1997 will be entirely the affair of the SAR government within
the scope of its high-degree autonomy.
</P>
<P>
However, Patten deliberately regarded the chief executive of
the future Hong Kong SAR as his successor and outlined ten items
for the work of the SAR executive body.
</P>
<P>
From his address, his attempt is obviously exposed: the smooth
transition is not his only aim, and all what he needs is a
successful transition, which tries to extend the colonial rule
beyond 1997 and influence the operation of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
To people's indignation, the address made much criticism and
maliciously attacked the people who love the motherland and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
With only nine months to go before Hong Kong's return to the
motherland, Sino-British relations are progressing to the
direction of the continuous improvment.
</P>
<P>
In the final and critical stage of the transitional period,
increasing cooperation between China and Britain, and guaranteing
a smooth transition has become the common aspiration of the all
Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
As the policy address goes against the wishes of the Hong Kong
people, and is widely divergent from the British government's
repeated expression of restoring and developing the Sino-British
cooperative relations, it has once again aroused new disputes in
Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
