<HEADLINE> Pakistan Calls for Multinational Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Benazir Bhutto, the prime
minister of Pakistan, called on Thursday for a multinational
conference in South Asia, that will include the five permanent
members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the 51st General Assembly, Bhutto noted that
while Kashmir dispute has led to four direct or indirect wars
between India and Pakistan, South Asia lacks a regional security
system.
</P>
<P>
She welcomed the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, saying that it
is exactly the kind of global measure for non-proliferation and
disarmament. She noted, however, India chose to veto the treaty in
the Geneva Conference on Disarmament and oppose the treaty in the
U.N. General Assembly last month.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to take this opportunity to propose to this
august Assembly that it endorse the convening of a multinational
dialogue for peace and security in South Asia, including the
participation of not only Pakistan and India, but the five
permanent members of the Security Council and other major powers
like Germany and Japan," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the multilateral conference could cover three critical
areas, the first of which is the resolution of the Kashmir dispute
and other bilateral problems between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The second is the promotion of conventional arms control and
confidence building measures and the third measure is to promote
nuclear restraint and arrest the danger of a nuclear arms race in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that such multilateral talks offer a frame-work for
genuine negotiations which can lead to a resolution of disputes,
arrest the nuclear threat, and promote prosperity in South Asia,"
she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
