<HEADLINE> A Taxing Time for Pascal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Pascal Weber was really shocked
when ordered to pay 115,352 francs (23,100 U.S. dollars) in tax
arrears accumulated since 1988.
</P>
<P>
.....He was not in France until April 1995!
</P>
<P>
He was threatened by the September 16 notice with the
confiscation of all his properties if he refused to pay the money.
</P>
<P>
Only after the Luxemburg shopkeeper went to the local tax
department did he learn that he had the same name, same birth date
and same security number as another man wanted for evading taxes.
</P>
<P>
His quandary didn't stop there. Eight days later, he found his
bank account had been frozen by the government.
</P>
<P>
Outraged, Weber launched a lawsuit at a local court in Moselle.
</P>
<P>
He called for the annulment of the freeze order, which is still
in force, and demanded 10,000 francs (2,000 U.S. dollars)
compensation for material losses and mental distress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
