<HEADLINE> Doctor's AIDS Infection Was Labor Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A French court today recognized a
report by a committee of experts who described the infection of a
doctor by the AIDS virus when he was conducting a surgery as "a
labor accident."
</P>
<P>
Doctor Patrick Cohen cut his finger during an operation on a
patient in May 1983, in Saint-Germain-en-Laye Hospital in Yveline,
west of Paris.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks later, Cohen, who was then 43 years old, began to
suffer from mono-nucleus infection, which is one of the
preliminary syndromes in AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
"At that time people did not really know about the
virus. Today, people would call it sero-conversion," Sabine
Paugam, Cohen's lawyer, told the court in Versailles.
</P>
<P>
"The recognition of the professional disease today has been
made without objection," the Tribunal of Social Security Affairs,
under the Versaille Tribunal, announced.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal had selected a new committee of experts in
February after a former committee rejected the thesis of a labor
accident.
</P>
<P>
Paugam said that the cause-and-result relationship between the
wound and the disease was "extremely well established" by the new
experts. Their report was submitted in early September to the
local authorities in charge of disease insurance.
</P>
<P>
After Cohen was found to be HIV-positive, the hospital
authorities contacted about 8,000 patients he had operated on from
1983 to 1994, and 3,000 of them had been tested for the
AIDS-causing virus.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who is now under treatment at home by an AIDS expert,
has launched a lawsuit against the government and the hospital for
"insufficient protection measures." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
