<HEADLINE> Peace Process in Balkans to Be Completed Soon: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav press said Thursday
the lifting of sanctions against Yugoslavia has indicated that the
implementation of the peace process for the former Yugoslavia
would soon be concluded.
</P>
<P>
The press said the lifting of the sanctions was the logical
consequence and result of the years of constructive and peaceful
policy of Yugoslavia and in particular Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council voted unanimously on Tuesday to lift
the sanctions against Yugoslavia. The overall trade embargo,
imposed in May 1992, was suspended last November but has crippled
the Yugoslav economy.
</P>
<P>
The Belgrade daily Politika said a great injury had been done
to Yugoslavia through the imposition of the sanctions, and their
lifting was crucial for the entire Balkans because they had
incurred great losses on Yugoslavia and its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
According to rough estimates, Yugoslavia suffered a direct loss
of 50 billion U.S. dollars and indirect loss of 150 billion U.S.
dollar due to the sanctions. Per capita income is now 1,000 U.S.
dollars, half of what it was in 1987. Foreign debt stands at about
8 billion dollars and almost half of the workforce are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia has every right now to expect that it will soon
secure the place that belongs to it in the United Nations, the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and other
international organizations and institutions," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It said one should not be too optimistic, however, about
further developments at this point, saying there was a lot to be
done before Yugoslavia finally returned to international financial
and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution, although lifted the comprehensive embargo,
does not release Belgrade's assets frozen abroad. The U.N.
Security Council also reserved the right to reimpose the sanctions
if the parties to last year's Dayton peace agreement fail to
adhere to the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The Belgrade daily Vecernje Novosti said Yugoslav people had
borne the brunt of the sanctions, going through tribulations
unrecorded in the recent history. The country's economy was
devastated, many people lost their jobs, while the society's most
sensitive strata -- the children and the elderly -- were severely
punished, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Borba, a Belgrade-based daily, stressed the importance of
Yugoslavia's consistent and constructive policy of peace.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia's reintegration into the United Nations and other
international organizations and institutions will soon be on the
agenda," the paper predicted.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has secured a great diplomatic victory, but has to
make great diplomatic efforts to put everything into order, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Dnevnik, a daily in Yugoslavia's northern city Novi Sad, said
Yugoslavia has again become a key factor of peace, stability and
good-neighborly relations in the turbulent Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all ill-meant wishes, pressure and the blockade,
Yugoslavia has been and will continue to be a country of
prosperity and a country with the future," the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
