<HEADLINE> EU Complains About Indonesia's Car Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
decided today to launch a formal complaint with the World Trade
Organization (WTO) over Indonesia's policy on car imports.
</P>
<P>
The decision follows this week's duty-free importation into
Indonesia of a consignment of automobiles from South Korea, which
were believed to have been assembled with Indonesian parts.
</P>
<P>
"The EU is concerned at the discrimination against European and
other foreign vehicles in favor of national vehicles," an EU
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is something of a paradox that with import tariffs as high
as 125 percent, the Indonesian government still feels that it
needs discriminatory measures to protect its industry," EU Trade
Commissioner Leon Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
The measures adopted by Indonesia breached the basic principles
of the multilateral trading system, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
