<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Down Sharply in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
dropped by 1.9 percent in August, the largest decline in two and
a half years, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline was seen by many analysts as a fresh evidence
of an economic slowdown in the second half of the year, because
factory orders are considered a key gauge of the manufacturing
strength in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for both durable and nondurable
goods totaled a seasonally adjusted 311.1 billion dollars in the
month, down from a revised 317.3 billion in July when orders had
jumped 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline was the steepest since a 2.2 percent drop in
January 1993.
</P>
<P>
The report said that factory orders for durable goods fell by
3.2 percent, the largest since a 3.4 percent drop in April 1995.
Nondurable goods such as food and fuel also fell by 0.4 percent,
the second decline in three months.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders decreased by 7.9 percent, led by falling
demand for both aircraft and automobiles. Electronic and other
electrical equipment were down by 5.6 percent and primary metals
by 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders decreased 0.3 percent, the first
decline since April. A shrinking backlog suggests businesses will
not have to increase production facilities and manpower to meet
demand.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a measure of current activity, managed an small 0.1
percent increase, compared to the 1.1 percent July advance.
Inventories rose by 0.3 percent following a 0.1 percent increase
in July.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve have been expecting that the U.S. economy
will moderate on its own and kept interest rates steady later last
month.
</P>
<P>
But recent economic data have been mixed. The new homes sale
soared by 8.3 percent in August, the largest in 10 years. And the
Index of Leading Economic Indicators, a gauge of future economic
activity in U.S., rose for the seventh straight month in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
