<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Beef Labeling Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Commission of the European
Union (EU) today adopted a proposal calling to label beef and beef
products so as to restore market confidence, said a spokesman of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the proposal suggested to introduce a
computerized database in each EU member states and a passport for
each animal which will allow the animal to be traced back to the
holdings it has been on.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU said the decision on whether or not to label
beef and beef products was optional for operators and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The label may include information concerning the animal, the
method of fattening and other information in relation to feeding.
</P>
<P>
By adopting these measures, the EU hopes to rebuild consumer
confidence in beef and beef products which has been seriously
damaged by the crisis of the Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy
(BSE) or the "mad cow" disease.
</P>
<P>
"If this identification and labeling system had been in
operation prior to the BSE crisis," Farm Commissioner Franz
Fischler, the designer of the proposal, said, "it is unlikely that
we would have seen the huge drop in beef consumption which
resulted from the scare."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Requests WTO Panel over Film Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
formally requested the World Trade Organization (WTO) to establish
a panel against Japan, accusing it of discriminating against
imports of photographic film and paper.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the meeting of the WTO Dispute Settlement
Body (DSB), the U.S. said the Japanese government "has established
and has maintained a series of interrelated measures over the past
three decades that have thwarted imports of photographic film and
paper."
</P>
<P>
According to it, Japan has adopted measures including
nontransparent restrictions to minimize or block market access by
foreign products through distribution system, failing to commit
itself to obligations under the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. said it made the request after formal bilateral
consultations in July failed to produce "a mutually acceptable
solution".
</P>
<P>
At the DSB meeting, Japan asked for further consultations with
the U.S., saying it believed that "the United States has not yet
exhausted all possibilities for a solution" through consultations
and that it "is not in a position to agree today to the
establishment of a panel."
</P>
<P>
Trade sources said that a panel would be established after the
next DSB meeting scheduled for October 16, unless a consensus
would be reached at the meeting against the U.S. request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
