<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Role Key to China's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- China deems teachers' role key to
its social and economic development, making efforts including
legislation and income-raising measures to improve their living
standards and social status.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, China issued the teachers law to ensure professional
qualification and rights of its teachers, who account for one
fifth of the global total.
</P>
<P>
Liu Bin, Deputy Minister of State Education Commission,
Thursday told the 45th session of the International Conference on
Education from September 30 to October 5 in Geneva that
particularly, the law lays principles concerning teachers' pay and
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In order to enhance teachers' living standards, the government
has for several times raised their wages and granted them special
allowance as well as preferential treatment concerning housing,
medical care and pension, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, in a way to enhance teachers' social status,
China's mass media has provided continued and extensive coverage
of outstanding teachers.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, China's teacher education and training
institutions have been funded by the government. Over the past
decade, these institutions provided over 4 million new teachers
for the country's primary and middle schools, while running
re-training programs for many of the in-service teachers.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts arise from a full awareness of the importance
of education to the country's future. Liu said China's goal at
present, as stated by Chinese Premier Li Peng in 1994, is to
achieve universal nine-year compulsory education and adult
literacy by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Government ministers and education experts from some 150
countries attending the education meeting are trying to define
ways to improve teachers' recruitment, training and career
opportunities. The UN Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) voiced concern over the decline worldwide in
teachers' living standards and social status.
</P>
<P>
Such a trend threatens to derail the promising gains in basic
education made since the start of this decade, said UNESCO, which
sponsored the meeting.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO estimated that by the year 2000, 9 million more
qualified will be needed in order to achieve universal primary
education globally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
