<HEADLINE> Moscow, Chechnya Agree to Set Up Joint Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and national security chief Aexander Lebed signed
a joint statement today together with Chechen separatist leader
Zeimkhan Yandarbiyev on the establishing of a joint commission,
which is to deal with further Chechen settlement.
</P>
<P>
According to television reports here, the commission will be
co-chaired by "experienced and competent persons, but not
politicians most probably."
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Chernomyrdin as saying that the commission
will engage in the extremely broad scope of activities, from the
implementation of President Boris Yeltsin's decrees on Chechnya
to the restoration of Chechnya's economy.
</P>
<P>
After signing ceremony, Yandarbiyev told reporters that the
Chechen separatists are going to adhere to previous military
accords signed in the Dagestani town of Khasavyurt by Lebed and
Chechen military chief Aslan Maskahdov.
</P>
<P>
Yandarbiyev said the settlement of political issues including
Chechnya's status has been postponed for a maximum of five
years. But the parties might reach an agreement before that, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Yandarbiyev arrived in Moscow earlier today for talks with
Chernomyrdin and Lebed over further Chechen settlement.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, Yeltsin met with Lebed to discuss Chechen
settlement. During the meeting, Yeltsin reportedly urged Lebed
to continue performing his duties and to work more assiduously
with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
