<HEADLINE> Addis Businessmen Demonstrate to Oppose Directive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen here
demonstrated for the second time today opposing the directive
issued by the Addis Ababa Regional Council fixing the prices of
verandahs, stalls and shops owned by it.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Ethiopian News Agency, the
demonstrators took to the major roads of Addis Ababa and shouted
slogans against the directive. They said the directive was devoid
of the consent and participation of the persons concerned.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators submitted their demands to parliament, the
House of People's Representatives and the Addis Ababa Regional
Council. They said their business should not be snatched away
for being kind to the have nots.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the House of People's Representatives Dawit
Yohannes said, evaluated in contrast with the price situation in
the world market, the price fixed by the Regional Council is
minimal.
</P>
<P>
He urged members of the business community to seek ways of
heightening their competitiveness in the free market.
</P>
<P>
The Addis Ababa businessmen held a demonstration on September
3, 1996 demanding the lifting of the directive. Later, Ethiopian
Prime Minister Meles Zenawi came out to defend the steps, saying
the measures taken by the the Addis Ababa region to fix the
prices of state-owned business centers in the capital were just
and correct. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
