<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Create Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The East African
Cooperation (EAC), which comprises Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, is
planning to create a regional free trade and investment zone.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by the three-day EAC trade conference
held in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, Samuel Sitta,
Director General of the Tanzania Investment Promotion Center,
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"The region, with a population of over 80 million people, is
potential for a single trade and investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by trade officials and businessmen from
the three east African countries, also recommended establishing
an east African Business Council and a special tribunal to settle
business disputes among the three EAC member countries.
</P>
<P>
"The Lake Victoria region has been identified as one of the
zones as a special development corridor," said the Tanzanian
official.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the market will not be closed to foreign
competitors, but, it is expected that east African businesses
will have a competitive advantage of the home market," said EAC
Executive Secretary Francis Muthaura after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Details about the free trade zone would be worked out by a
technical committee under the EAC secretariat, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha meeting also recommended reviewing and updating
trade and investment codes of the three countries by June 1997 to
speed up business registration procedures.
</P>
<P>
Other proposals were stepping up the development of the
infrastructure including roads, railways, ports, energy supply
and telecommunications, and promotion of cross border trade.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting is very fruitful," said Muthaura, explaining that
his organization, born six months ago, would be targeted at
harmonizing polices of the three governments to create a
conducive environment for economic integration in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
