<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Leader Defuses Serious Challenge to His Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLACKPOOL, ENGLAND, October 3 (Xinhua) -- British Labor leader
Tony Blair came through his only serious challenge of the Party
Conference last night as the call for higher spending on pension
was defeated by a three-to-two majority, according to the formal
result of the card vote released this morning.
</P>
<P>
Barbara Castle, the former Social Services Secretary, vowed at
the eve of the Conference to fight for higher pension during the
annual gathering.
</P>
<P>
She brushed aside a bid by Labor leaders asking her to give up
the proposal over her call for the restoration of the link between
pensions and earnings.
</P>
<P>
The threat of defeat for Tony Blair on pensions receded at the
second day of the Conference which opened on September 30, after
two of the larger trade unions decided to back the party
leadership's commitment to create a commission that would review
the future of the state pension "as a matter of urgency" if it
wins the general election.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the general union (TGWU) and Unison, the public
service union, agreed to back the proposal and remit two more
radical motions to the national executive committee for further
consideration.
</P>
<P>
During the debate, Barbara Castle criticized Harriet Harman,
the Shadow Social Security Secretary, and Gordon Brown, the Shadow
Chancellor. Attacking Brown's ambition to cut the rate of tax to
10 percent for low earners, she said it would not give a penny to
the three million pensioners who were too poor to pay income tax.
</P>
<P>
However, the Labor leadership was tough on Castle's demand for
a 3.5 billion pounds (5.25 billion US dollars) package to increase
the income of all pensioners.
</P>
<P>
A statement released today by the Labor Party's National
Executive Commission stresses "the Labor Party can and will give
no manifesto or other commitments on finance for any decisions
that could only be made in the light of economic circumstances".
</P>
<P>
The statement also says the promised review will examine the
proposals of the National Pensioners' Convention "as well as other
reforms of our welfare state in the light of the public finances
at the time".
</P>
<P>
Announcing the statement, Harman said Labor was determined to
improve the position of pensioners but "would not make promises it
could not keep".
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the pension debate, the British paper The Daily
Telegraph said "Lady Castle wins hearts of the delegates but not
the vote of them". "Governments are starting to realize that a
decline in the ratio of workers to pensioners means that
earnings-related pensions funded on a pay-as-you-earn basis cannot
be sustained into the next century," the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
