<HEADLINE> Greece, Cyprus to Hold Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Cyprus will hold two
joint military exercises from October 4-8, it was confirmed here
today.
</P>
<P>
After two-hour talks with his visiting Cyprus counterpart
Costas Iliades, Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopulos told
reporters that the joint military exercises, code-named
"nikiforos" and "toxotis" will be held as scheduled on an
"enlarged basis with the participation of all the services of the
Greek armed forces".
</P>
<P>
The exercises will be held in Greece and in the government-
controlled areas of Cyprus respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The holding of the exercises will contribute in the best
possible way to safeguarding the effectiveness of the two
countries' defense capabilities," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos announced that he would visit Cyprus in November
in order "to shape the basis for more determined steps in the
defense cooperation between the two countries, in order for the
relevant political agreement to be put into practice, since this
is the top priority of the Greek government".
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus signed a joint defense pact in 1993, which
provides for the holding of joint military exercises and other
cooperation in the military fields.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot defense minister said that the implementation of
the joint defense doctrine "is aimed at deterrence and
strengthening Cyprus' negotiating position in any political
dialogue for a peaceful and viable solution to the Cyprus
problem."
</P>
<P>
Iliades also said that Nicosia accepted dialogue also at a
military level, but only on the condition that it was with the
Turkish commander of the occupation forces in northern Cyprus and
without the participation of the Turkish Cypriot military
commander. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
