<HEADLINE> Sarajevo, Belgrade Fully Normalize Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY) today fully normalized their
relations by agreeing to establish diplomatic relations at
ambassador's level and solving all problems over the succession of
the former Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic signed a common declaration in the Elysee
Palace in the presence of French President Jacques Chirac and many
journalists, burying a history of hatred in the past five years
between the two former Yugoslav republics.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to guarantee the freedom of travel
into each other's country by the people of Bosnia and FRY with the
cancellation of visa requirement, and to push forward economic and
trade relations between them.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia and the FRY will also support a two-year international
plan to consolidate peace in Bosnia, which will be formally
adopted by the international community before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said that the FRY wishes to turn the page of
confrontation with Bosnia and open a new page of cooperation and
progress, while his Bosnian counterpart said that he has signed a
document which is full of substance and which he wishes to put
into work soon.
</P>
<P>
While expressing his joy over the normalization of relations
between Bosnia and FRY, Chirac expressed his wish that the FRY
fully reintegrate into the international community, while Bosnia
can maintain its full territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic and Milosevic held two meetings today in the state
guest house of Hotel de Marigny before signing the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The summit was held after Bosnia held its presidential election
in which Izetbegovic was elected head of a collegiate presidency,
while the United Nations has lately lifted its economic embargo on
the FRY.
</P>
<P>
Technical experts of the two countries will finalize the
agreements reached at today's summit in accordance with the
international law, said French officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
