<HEADLINE> China Disabled Persons Federation Wins Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The China Disabled
Persons Federation received here today the 1996 Alexander Gralnick
Memorial Award for its work in promoting community-based care and
rehabilitation for over 200,000 mentally ill citizens with serious
mental disabilities.
</P>
<P>
This was the third time China won the award from the World
Association for Psychosocial Rehabilitation. In 1993 and 1994,
Professors Yan Heqin, Zhang Minyuan and Chen Yanfang received the
Alxander Gralnick Memorial Award, according to Martin Gittelman
advisor to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that China has developed an effective system for
mental illness with village doctors serving patients directly,
experts providing guidance for village doctors and the China
Disabled Persons Federation offering assistance to the experts. In
treatment, China has combined traditional therapy with modern
medicine, achieving good results.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the past five years, over 200,000 mental ill
citizens have been rehabilitated. In the next five year, China
plans to rehabilitate 1.2 million patients.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the China Disabled Persons Federation at
the awards ceremony of the World Association for Psychosocial
Rehabilitation today, Zhang Fengkun of the Chinese Permanent
Mission to the United Nations said China has about 60 million
people with disabilities, including 2 million with mental illness.
The Chinese government and the federation always showed concern to
the status of those people.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has adopted series of measures and the
comprehensive prevention and rehabilitation of mental illness in
an open and socialized way for treatment, she said.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, over 450,000 people with mental illness
received rehabilitation and social service through the community
based rehabilitation project. China was implementing a new program
on disability in the current Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) period.
</P>
<P>
China would work closely with the World Association of
Psychosocial Rehabilitation towards the common goal, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
