<HEADLINE> Angola's Savimbi Slated for Absence at SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Angola's former rebel leader
Jonas Savimbi has been slated for failing to attend the
just-concluded Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Summit held here.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the ruling People's Liberation Movement today
accused Savimbi, leader of the former rebel movement, National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), of "lacking
political will and zest" for furthering the Angolan peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference in Luanda that Savimbi disappointed
all the SADC leaders, including South African President Nelson
Mandela, who gathered for the first time in the Angolan capital
on Wednesday to discuss the country's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi had sent a letter to the meeting explaining why he
could not attend. But he was not pardoned by the regional
leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day meeting, the SADC leaders were briefed
about the recent progress of the Angolan peace process as well as
the major obstacles that stalked the formation of a union
government and army.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique, the regional organization urged Savimbi
to abide by the peace accord signed two years ago to finally
bring peace to Angola torn apart by nearly 20 years of civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
