<HEADLINE> Russian Premier Praises Talks with Chechen Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin has praised his talks with Chechen separatist leader
Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev held here today, noting that the two sides
agreed to intensify bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local reporters following his meeting with
Yandarbiyev, Chernomyrdin described today's decision on the
formation of a mixed commission of high-ranking leaders from both
sides as a big step forward in the process of a peaceful
settlement in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"A big step forward was taken in the direction we defined,"
Chernomyrdin said, adding that "on a number of matters we came to
a common opinion."
</P>
<P>
However, he went to say, "there also remain differences in
approaches." "We do not agree on everything," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a special commission is being formed and
Russian President Boris Yeltsin will approve the list of its
members and commission regulations in a few days.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the mixed commission is to resolve the
problems related to the establishment of normal living conditions
for thousands of citizens of Russia and Chechnya, the Russian
premier said.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting also focused on matters related to the
withdrawal of federal (Russian) troops and the demilitarization of
Chechnya, the prevention of persecution on political and ethnic
grounds, and combating criminal groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin stressed, however, that Russia's territorial
integrity, the inviolability of its frontiers, including
administrative dividing lines, and the operation of the federal
constitution cannot be used as bargaining chips.
</P>
<P>
He said military matters must be settled on the basis of the
June 25 presidential decree with due account to the security of
Russia and its borders.
</P>
<P>
"Chechnya is an internal affair of Russia," he said, adding
that a balanced policy of all branches of power in Russia should
result in a comprehensive set of measures to restore peace and law
in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Russian security chief Alexander Lebed and Akhmed Zakayev, one
of the Chechen separatist leaders, also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Yandarbiyev and his team came to Moscow for the talks earlier
this morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
