<HEADLINE> Chirac Arrives in Naples for Summit Meeting on Lire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
arrived in Naples this afternoon for a summit Friday with Italian
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, which is expected to be focused on
the entry of lire into the European Monetary Union (EMU),
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Lire became the center of a quarrel earlier this week between
France and Italy after Chirac repeatedly rapped the monetary
policy of Italy, particularly what he called "competitive
devaluation" of lire.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides made some gestures of appeasement before
Chirac set off for the Italian resort city lying beside the Vesuve
volcano which destroyed the Roman city of Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro hosted a dinner in honor of Chirac this evening in a
18th century palace built by the former French Bourbon royal
family on a hill overlooking Naples and the volcano.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said today that the
fundamental interests of Italy and France are "similar" with each
other and that the two countries can play a supplementary role to
each other.
</P>
<P>
Prodi will show Chirac the "dynamism" of the Italian economy in
international market and will stress the fact that the value of
lire has risen by 10 percent in the past one year, said local
observers.
</P>
<P>
He will also expose to Chirac Italy's 1997 austerity budget
plan which he said will allow Rome to meet the criteria set by the
Maastricht Treaty for entering the EMU on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italy also wishes to return to the European Monetary System by
spring next year, but Prodi said that this issue will not be
discussed at the Naples summit because it concerns the 15 European
Union members.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse quoted former Italian Prime Minister
Lamberto Dini as saying that the Naples summit will be "excellent"
and that beyond the differences over Italy's monetary policy,
there is an overall agreement between the two countries over
European issues.
</P>
<P>
France canceled its annual summit meeting with Italy last year
because of Rome's criticism of its nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Among other things to be discussed at the summit, there could
be the reform of European institutions, Italy's expected entry
into the Schengen treaty in March next year, reform of NATO, the
fight against organized crimes, the Middle East problem, Bosnia
and cooperation among Mediterranean countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
