<HEADLINE> Yemen Welcomes Arbitration Agreement with Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Yemen expressed welcome for the
signing of an arbitration agreement today between Yemen and
Eritrea for resolving the conflict over the disputed Greater
Hanish Island, and its appreciation of the French mediation
efforts in this respect.
</P>
<P>
This came in a statement by Yemeni Deputy Foreign Minister
Abdou Ali al Rahman to the Yemeni news agency.
</P>
<P>
Al Rahman said that the agreement stipulated the establishment
of an arbitration court in conformity with international law,
adding that the two parties had pledged to respect the court's
verdict and to refrain from any action or military activity by
one party against the other until the ruling was made.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni deputy foreign minister pointed out that the
agreement stipulated that the commitments of the two parties
shall be effective until the court ruling was implemented.
</P>
<P>
The court is to be composed of five judges, with each party
appointing two, and the fifth, the chairman, will be chosen by
virtue of an understanding between the four judges, according to
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Al Rahman added that Yemen and Eritrea had jointly agreed that
the arbitration court would be seated in London, Britain, for
practical reasons. But he did not elaborate on the reasons.
</P>
<P>
He added that today's signing of the related agreement in the
French capital of Paris is the outcome of what he called as
persistent efforts on the part of Yemen and the French government.
</P>
<P>
Yemen and Eritrea signed an agreement in France in May to
settle a clash last December over three Red Sea islands --
Greater Hanish, Lesser Hanish and Zuqar -- claimed by both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have credited France with helping to broker the
agreement through shuttle diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The disputed islands are about 160 kilometers (100 miles)
north of Bab el-Mandeb at the southern entrance to the Red
Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
