<HEADLINE> Britain to Host London Bosnia Conference in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain announced today that it
will host a major international conference on Bosnia in December
in London to decide peace implementation arrangements for 1997.
</P>
<P>
"This will follow the format of the Peace Implementation
Conference held in London in December 1995, and will assemble some
50 countries and international agencies, including the
newly-elected Bosnian leaders," the British Foreign Office said in
a statement today.
</P>
<P>
The December 4-5 meeting will be chaired by Foreign Secretary
Malcolm Rifkind together with Minister for Overseas Development
Baroness Chalker.
</P>
<P>
"The London conference will take decisions on the various
threads of international civilian involvement in Bosnia next year,
in the light of commitments by the parties on the future
implementation of Dayton," it added.
</P>
<P>
But it noted that the conference will not decide on any future
military presence in Bosnia after the current NATO-led peace
Implementation Force (IFOR) leaves on December 20, and decision on
any post-IFOR military presence will be taken by NATO's North
Atlantic Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
