<HEADLINE> Egypt Not Optimistic About Peace Process Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here today that Egypt, like the Palestinians, was not
optimistic about the Middle East peace process following a
four-way summit in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who returned home today after leading Egypt's
delegation to the 51st U.N. General Assembly in New York, said
that many European and Asian countries were sharing that view
with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The only indication that some progress could be made in the
peace march lay in the fact that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu agreed at the
Washington summit to resume Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
Sunday, Moussa said in statements carried by Egypt's news agency
MENA.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Netanyahu failed to reach agreement on any
outstanding issues at the summit which was also attended by
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Jordan's King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called the two-day summit, which ended Wednesday, in
an effort to save the Mideast peace process following an outbreak
of violence in occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The failure of the Washington summit was due to the Israeli
stance at the meeting, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs would not give anything for free, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's decision
not to participate in the summit was a strong sign of the Arab
rage and protest against the Israeli government's backtracking on
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
