<HEADLINE> UN Team to Report on Bakassi Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations team that has
just visited Nigeria and Cameroun on the disputed Bakassi
Peninsula will report its finding next week, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted UN Spokesperson Sylvana Foa as saying that
the team, back to New York on Saturday, is now preparing its
report and will soon submit it to UN Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the report will be made public, the spokesperson
said, "(even) if the whole report is not made public, we
certainly will get a readout of it that we will be able to give
you."
</P>
<P>
During its visit, the four-member U.N. team met with Nigerian
and Camerounian officials and heard their points of views on the
disputed oil-rich peninsula. It also met with Togolese President
Gnassingbe Eyadema, who has been mediating the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The team also made a trip to the disputed area. Its head Omar
Halim had said that the team had come not as a judge, but only to
help maintain peace and security in the area before the
International Court of Justice could in Hague give its final
rule. 
</P>
