<HEADLINE> SADC to Take Steps on Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) will send a ministerial delegation to attend a
United Nations Security Council meeting next Friday to assess the
Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
The SADC delegation would include foreign ministers from
Mozambique, Angola, Zimbabwe and South Africa, Mozambican
President Joaquim Chissano said here today in a joint press
conference held together with Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos at Luanda's international airport before his departure.
</P>
<P>
"SADC will take joint measures to push forward the Angolan
peace process," said Chissano who had attended the one-day SADC
summit meeting held for the first time in the Angolan capital on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SADC groups South Africa, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Angola,
Zambia, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland, Malawi, Tanzania
and Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
The summit, attended by the heads of state and government from
10 out of the 12 SADC member countries except Tanzania and
Malawi, urged the former rivals at the 20-year-old Angolan civil
war to step up efforts in forging a union government and army.
</P>
<P>
However, the regional leaders were disappointed at the fact
that former rebel UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi, a key player of the
Angolan peace process, had failed to appear at the summit.
</P>
