<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Premier Outlines Aims of Army Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin today outlined four aims of the country's army
reform, and admitted that economic and social-political
difficulties had exacerbated the situation in the army.
</P>
<P>
Interfax news agency said the Prime Minister was chairing a
military meeting to consider economic problems in the armed forces
and their combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the first task was to adjust the composition,
structure and size of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The second was to knit a personnel core for a technically
well-equipped, flexibly controlled and professionally trained
military capable of removing threats emerging in key strategic
directions and creating conditions for mobilizing bigger forces to
repel large-scale aggression.
</P>
<P>
The third task was the full and unconditional equipping of the
armed forces with funding depending on budget resources.
</P>
<P>
The fourth task was to keep troops in high readiness for
purposes of defense and other direct functions.
</P>
<P>
The premier was quoted as saying that serious financial
problems had resulted in a shortage of funds for servicemen's
pay, food, energy and other supplies. These problems had become
chronic.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of government officials, the structure of the
armed forces needed serious reform, and to be brought in line with
the military-political and economic situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin was absent from today's meeting because
of illness and his coming heart bypass operation.
</P>
<P>
It was attended by the presidential chief of staff, Anatoly
Chubais, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Defense Minister Igor
Rodionov, Interior Minister Anatoly Kulikov, Federal Border
Service Director Andrei Nikolayev, Defense Council Secretary Yuri
Baturin and other council members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
