<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide Loan for Power Project in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
agreed to provide a soft loan of some 152 million U.S. dollars for
the implementation of a medium-sized hydroelectric project in
western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Letters of exchange on the loan were signed here today by
representatives of the two governments, according to the Nepali
Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the 144-megawatt Kali Gandaki project, located
about 100 kilometers west of Kathmandu, is expected to begin early
next year and will be completed in January 2001, the ministry said
in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered one of the most viable and low-cost
medium-sized hydroelectric projects in Nepal, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank earlier had agreed to provide a soft
loan of nearly 111 million dollars for the 453 million dollar
project, according to the ministry.  
