<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Industrial Output Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's industrial output
grew more than eight percent in the year until last August, the
National Statistical Office (NSO) said today.
</P>
<P>
The NSO attributed a robust increase in industrial output to
strong domestic demand for oil products and increased exports of
automobiles, office equipment and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Production of automobiles increased by 17.9 percent, office
equpment by 28.6 percent, chemicals by 11.4 percent and oil
products by 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a clear sign of the deepening "industrial polarization,"
output of the heavy and chemical sectors surged 11.6 percent in
the year to August, while light industries declined 3.6 percent,
an NSO official said.
</P>
<P>
In August, manufacturing industries operated at an average 83.5
percent of capacity, a 0.8 percentage point higher than in July.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale and retail sales rose 6.3 percent in August from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, unemployment increased slightly, from 1.8 percent in
July to 1.9 percent in August, the office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
