<HEADLINE> Egypt, Turkey Urge Israel to Refrain from Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Turkey today urged
Israel to refrain from any acts that could damage and jeopardize
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued at the end of talks between Egyptian
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and his visiting Turkish
counterpart Necmettin Erbakan, the two countries demanded that
Israel close the tunnel which it opened near Al Aqsa Mosque in
Jerusalem last month.
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on Israel to abide by its commitments
under the signed Palestinian-Israeli agreements and resume peace
negotiations in accordance with what was agreed upon at the 1991
Madrid peace conference and relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers urged Israel not to resort to use of
force, according to the statement carried by Egypt's news agency
MENA.
</P>
<P>
Israel's opening of the tunnel triggered several days of
clashes between Palestinians and Israeli troops, which left more
than 70 people dead. The situation in the Palestinian territories
has remained tense.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Erbakan criticized what he called Israel's
provocative actions in Jerusalem, saying that these actions could
undermine the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel's opening of the tunnel was unacceptable to
Turkey and the whole Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, who ended his visit to Egypt today, also met with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Turkey today signed four agreements on economic,
trade, judicial and investment cooperation following the talks
between Erbakan and Ganzouri, also attended by government
ministers and officials from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first leg of Erbakan's three-nation African
tour, which will also take him to Libya and Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
