<HEADLINE> No Game Dies in S.African Bush Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- No game died in the worst
bush fire of the past 40 years in South Africa's Kruger National
Park, park spokesman Chris Van Der Linde said today.
</P>
<P>
"We only found the carcass of an impala, but its death could
not be linked to the fire," he told the press.
</P>
<P>
Linde said there were still isolated fires, but the danger of
runaway blazes was over. "We will continue to see smoke for the
next few days, mostly from smoldering logs," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bush fires caused by lightening on September 25 have destroyed
up to 15 percent of Kruger National Park.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the fires were not as devastating as
initially feared. Game managed to escape the flames, and no
private or park property was damaged.
</P>
<P>
Last bush fire occurred in the park in 1955.
</P>
<P>
The park, founded in 1926, covers 20,000 square kilometres
with the greatest diversity of wildlife of any park in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
