<HEADLINE> Myanmar Regrets U.S. Visa Restrictions on Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government today
expressed deep regrets at a U.S. decision to impose visa
restrictions on certain Myanmar nationals and retaliated by
suspending the issuance of visas to U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement issued here, the Myanmar Foreign Ministry
said the United States is giving undue and unwarranted pressure on
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made in reaction to the U.S. government's
proclamation Thursday that entry into the United States by certain
Myanmar nationals was suspended.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said the U.S. proclamation negatively affects
the existing bilateral relations and can be considered as an
attempt to interfere in Myanmar's internal affairs and a means of
exerting pressure.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the allegations included in the U.S.
proclamation are not in conformity with the real situation and the
progress achieved in the country and are ignoring the positive
political, economic and social development taking place in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government categorically rejects the proclamation,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement stated that Myanmar has suspended the issuance
of all types of visas to U.S. citizens except as required by
treaty obligations and officials and other supporting staffs
assigned to the U.S. mission in Myanmar.  
</P>
