<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are Business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Turkey signed today four agreements on
economic, trade, judicial and investment cooperations.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were inked after Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
El-Ganzouri met here with his visiting Turkish counterpart
Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan is on a three-nation African tour which will also take
him to Libya and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The food processing and packaging equipment
market in Saudi Arabia is presently at an annual growth of 6 to 8
percent, suggested a study by the U.S. Consulate General in
Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The food processing and packaging is turning into a high volume
industry in the Gulf country in order to meet the demands of 20
million consumers, the study report said.
</P>
<P>
The sector has received investment commitments of over 1
billion U.S. dollars, and the United States commands more than 15
percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has a 5 billion dollar food import market
potential.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Minister of Supply Ahmed Goweily announced on Thursday
that the International Monetary Fund's Board of Directors would
meet next week to assess Egypt's final stage economic structural
reform program. The third bracket of Egypt's debts estimated at
about 4 billion dollars would probably be dropped.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Executive Body of Investment Authority said
that 95 percent of partnership agreement items with the EU have
been completed. Regarding the rest 5 percent, 39 projects were
submitted to Italy.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A savage price war among the privately-owned
gasoline stations in Riyadh have forced five fueling centers out
of business.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's government prices gasoline at 60 halalas (0.16
dollars) a liter, but some of the stations charge seven to ten
halalas less to lure as many as possible customers, the Saudi
daily Arab News reported.
</P>
<P>
Some gasoline station owners complained that the
lower-than-cost prices have driven them to the verge of
bankruptcy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
