<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Says No More Yasukuni Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto has decided not to visit Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine because
his July visit touched off widespread protests from other Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
"I must be careful in future if (my visiting the shrine) would
cause suspicion of, or trouble to, Japan," Kyodo News quoted
Hashimoto as saying. He was being interviewed by the local press
as president of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), ahead of the
October 20 general election for the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto visited Yasukuni in July, becoming the first
incumbent Japanese prime minister to do so since Yasuhiro Nakasone
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Yasukuni is the place where memorial ceremonies are held
for Japan's war dead, including class-A war criminals such as
militarist leader Hideki Tojo.
</P>
<P>
Visits to the shinto religions place by incumbent cabinet
members have always caused criticism from Japan's neighboring
countries, such as China, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, and South Korea, which suffered bitterly under the Japanese
militarist empire before and during World War II.
</P>
<P>
China has lodged protests against the LDP, the dominant force
within the tripartite ruling coalition, over the party's election
platform that favors visits by cabinet ministers to Yasukuni,
and asserts Japanese claim to China's islands in the East China
Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
