<HEADLINE> Third IIAS General Assembly to Open in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Challenges facing administrative
managements in the 21st century will be the theme of the four-day
third General Assembly of the International Institute of
Administrative Sciences (IIAS), which opens here on October 8.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Chinese Ministry of Personnel, the sponsor
of the conference, said that participants at the meeting will
discuss ways to promote efficiency, streamline administrative
structure and decentralize power.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, more than 700 specialists and government
officials who are seeking the self-improvement of government
bodies will attempt to redefine the function and position of
government and to search for ways to strengthen the government's
sense of responsibility and risks, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"For its close links with governmental affairs, the conference
has drawn great attention from both the political and the academic
circles," the ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 500 overseas delegates from some 100 countries and
regions and international bodies who are attending the meeting, 50
are ministerial officials and renowned specialists. Nearly 200
Chinese delegates are scheduled to participate.
</P>
<P>
The official said the country has attempted to reform its
administrative mechanism and personnel system over the past decade
in order to facilitate the establishment and development of the
market economy, and has nearly reached its goal.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he said, many countries are also restructuring
government bodies for higher efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"By learning from the advanced experiences of others through
this conference, China will further its reforms," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The IIAS, founded in 1930, is the highest academic body in the
administrative sciences field, with 102 member countries and
national-level sub-institutes, 10 inter-governmental
organizations, many group members and individual members.
</P>
</TEXT>
