<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Alliance Favors One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's opposition Inter-Party
Alliance has resolved to field one presidential candidate in the
general elections scheduled for later this year, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached at a meeting of leaders of the
seven-party alliance in Lusaka on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Roger Chongwe, the alliance chairman and Leader of the Liberal
Progressive Party, said in an interview that the alliance members
had agreed on an electoral pact based on ''one alliance candidate
in the areas where the parties are popular.''
</P>
<P>
He noted, ''The agreement is on one presidential candidate
representing the alliance rather than all the parties fielding
candidates. Negotiations for selecting candidates from the
opposition alliance members who may have an equal chance of
success will depend on the quality and calibre of the
aspirants.''
</P>
<P>
He added that the secretaries of the alliance would work out
modalities of the strategies for the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Kaunda, former republican President and leader of the
major oppition party, the United National Independent party, said
in the meeting that he would contest the republican presidency
despite his being disqualified by a controversial constitution
ammendment because of his Malawian parentage as his party's
national council had adopted a resolution on his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties are urging for the repeal of the
constitution amendment which bars Zambians of foreign parentage
to contest the republican presidency. But the ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy maintains that the constitution amendment
is a law as it was adopted in parliament and signed by the
president and everybody should abide by it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
