<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ozone Hole Widens in Antarctic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The earth surface affected by the
ozone hole over the Antarctic has increased to more than 20
million square kilometers, twice the area of all Europe, the World
Meteorological Organization (WMO) said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the WMO Antarctic ozone bulletin, the increase
occurred earlier this year than in the previous few years.
</P>
<P>
In the past two or three days, ozone concentrations have
slipped to a more than 45 percent deficiency over nearly the
entire Antarctic continent.
</P>
<P>
Satellite data showed that south of 65 degrees south, the ozone
concentration was the lowest in the past four to five years. In
the 17 to 22 km layer above earth, all ozone was practically
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
WMO experts believed that with the increasing
chlorine in the stratosphere, the ozone destruction would
become worse with certain circulation patterns,
especially when stratospheric temperatures were very low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attention Called for Preventing Rheumatic Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A new survey has shown that the
incidence of rheumatic diseases in some parts of China has risen
to over 18 percent, a new threat to people in cold and damp areas.
</P>
<P>
A special committee on rheumatic diseases under the China's
Chinese-Western Medicine Society started the survey of four types
of rheumatic diseases in 17 provinces, municipalities, and
autonomous regions in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Doctors from the committee have visited 87,127 people in the
areas, and found 16,004 rheumatic patients, accounting for 18.64
percent. Rheumatic arthritis was the major ailment, accounting for
16.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that in the country's very cold province
Heilongjiang, the incidence of rheumatic diseases was as high as
30 percent, while in damp areas like Hainan province, it
went up to 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
It showed that the incidence of the diseases among officers and
soldiers in the People's Liberation Army, and workers in textiles,
alloys, chemicals and petroleum was 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The data achieved from the survey has provided valuable
information for preventing and treating the diseases, according to
the committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
