<HEADLINE> South Korea's Inflation Rate Hits 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's inflation rate, as
measured by consumer prices, increased to 4.7 percent as of the
end of last month, surpassing the government control target for
the entire year of 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance and Economy said today that in
September alone, the inflation rate rose 0.3 percent, bringing the
nine-month total to 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the prices of gasoline and other oil products increasing
by an average of 2.04 percent this month, the rate would continue
to increase for the remainder of the year, a ministry official
said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the inflation rate exceeded the price control target
for the year as of the end of September, a bumper harvest was
expected to contribute to comparatively stable prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government would continue its price stabilization
efforts during the rest of the year, said the official. 
</P>
