<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus Attention on Rural Surplus Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China is working to provide jobs
for its huge force of rural surplus labor, in a bid to further
develop the rural economy and narrow the gap between it and the
urban economy.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics put the size of rural surplus labor
currently in China at 130 million people.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference today in Beijing, Wang Zhe, vice-director
of the Employment Department under the Ministry of Labor, said
that there are two solutions for the employment problem of China's
excess workforce.
</P>
<P>
"One is to help them find jobs at or near their homes. The
other is to shift some of them to new places that are short of
labor, like the cities," he explained.
</P>
<P>
But the latter solution is not always satisfactory, he pointed
out, as cities have only limited job opportunities and are
currently under great pressure to re-employ laid-off workers from
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He added that government macro-control over the labor market,
which can coordinate urban and rural employment and keep a
"reasonable and orderly" labor flow from the countryside to the
cities, is still necessary in China.
</P>
<P>
He praised a pilot project for rural employment, which was
launched jointly in 1991 by the Ministry of Labor, the Ministry of
Agriculture, and the Development Research Center of the State
Council, China's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The project now covers over 100 cities and counties in eight
provinces across China, including Sichuan, Guangdong, Hubei,
Jiangsu, Anhui, Shandong, Hebei, and Gansu.
</P>
<P>
"In the past five years, all the areas that carried out the
project have seen a noticeable drop in rural surplus labor, as
well as a general rise in the income of the farmers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministries and the research center will convene a
national meeting in Beijing in mid-October to help spread the
experiences of these labor and agricultural officials across the
country.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first national meeting on rural employment since
the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"After the meeting, the whole country will focus attention on
the employment issue of rural surplus labor," said Wang Zhe.
</P>
<P>
China's Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) maintains that the
country should be able to shift 40 million people among the rural
surplus labor to non-agricultural sectors in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"Needless to say, it's a very hard job to reach this target,"
said Wang. "But with enough attention and effort from the
government, the prospects of rural employment are still quite
bright."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Reconciliation among </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
called on Afghan warring groups to stop fighting and seek
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati issued the appeal at a
press conference here, saying: "What is important for us in
Afghanistan is peace and security on the basis of national
reconciliation among different groups."
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here hold that Iran felt increasingly worried about
the situation in its neighboring Afghanistan since the militia
Taliban seized Kabul and the Rabbani government fled the capital
on September 28.
</P>
<P>
Velayati noted, "It is not our job to decide the destiny of
the people in Afghanistan and they have to decide by themselves."
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to directly answer the question whether
Tehran would recognize the new government in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Taliban militia appeared to have
brought the capital city Kabul under full control since last week
when it announced to set up an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
As far as Iran is concerned, he said, "Iran doesn't have any
specific priority in any groups. Our principle is to stop
fighting and try to have peaceful settlement in that country."
</P>
<P>
Velayati claimed that none of the ethnic groups can run
the country alone in the absence of contributions from other
groups.
</P>
<P>
He also asked foreign countries to keep hands out of
Afghanistan, asserting, "Foreign intervention in Afghanistan
will aggravate the situation."
</P>
<P>
" History in that country shows that foreign intervention
always fails and would not be in the interests of the Afghan
people," he said without mentioning any country by name.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister said that regarding the events
there, Iran is in touch with the neighboring countries of
Afghanistan, including China, Pakistan and Russia,
</P>
<P>
"Our policy is neutrality toward Afghanistan and it is not
our job to say who should run the government and who should
not," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out,"We want a government that would have the
support of all ethnic groups and religious factions there."
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly criticized the United States and Pakistan
for their support to the Taliban militant students.
Tehran holds that the Taliban's advancement was not possible
without the logistic and command support from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian authorities called the Taliban a project
masterminded by the United States, partly financed by Saudi Arabia
and implemented by Pakistan with the aim of curbing Iran's
influence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
