<HEADLINE> Filipino Death Convicts to Number 300 by Year-End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two criminals were
sentenced to death in September, bringing the total number of
death-row inmates to 234 in the country, the Philippine News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The number of persons convicted of heinous crimes and meted out
the death penalty will top the 300-mark by the end of this year,
according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
It said at least 87 accused drug traffickers, including 23
foreigners, and some 200 accused rapists will be up as candidates
for the death row for the resolution of courts in the next three
to six years.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government resumed the death penalty in 1994 in
order to stop the increasingly serious crime rate in the country.
However, the first death penalty will not be executed until next
year and social security in the country has not shown any
improvement despite the government's efforts.  
</P>
