<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest In Science In Major North China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey in the North
China port city of Tianjin shows that people there seem just about
as eager to learn about science and technology as are people in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted last December by the Tianjin Science
and Technology Association to find out how Tianjin residents get
scientific and technological information, what their attitudes to
science and technology are, and how much they understand about
science.
</P>
<P>
It involved workers in manufacturing and the commercial
sectors, armed police, students, scientists, technicians, and
government officials, more than half of whom said they knew the
terms 'greenhouse effect', 'molecule', 'computers and software',
and 'information superhighway'.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about what a surperconductor is, 46.3
percent answered correctly; and about which field DNA belongs to,
50.5 percent were correct.
</P>
<P>
The survey did show, however, that nearly half of the
respondents knew little about 'probability'.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin Science and Technology Association also compared
the results of its survey with a similar survey conducted in the
U.S. in 1992, and found that Americans pay more attention to
scientific and technological information than people in Tianjin
do, but that the difference was not significant.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that newspapers and television serve as
a major channel through which people in Tianjin learn about
science and technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
