<HEADLINE> Malaysian Marine Police Shoot at Indonesian Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Marine Police
fired two rounds of tear gas at an Indonesian fishing vessel which
tried to flee after it was caught fishing in Malaysian waters near
Pulau Perak, about 60 nautical miles from Langkawi, yesterday,
police said today.
</P>
<P>
The tear gas shells exploded on the boat and the escaping gas
forced the skipper to stop the vessel, the Langkawi-based Northern
Zone Marine Police chief Zakaria Embi said today.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred when the Marine Police on a patrol boat
he commanded spotted the Indonesian vessel about three nautical
miles off the island, and several crew members of the vessel were
seen pulling up a fishing net, Zakaria was quoted by the Malaysian
national news agency, Bernama, as saying.
</P>
<P>
When the Marine Police boat attempted to draw alongside, the
fishing vessel suddenly picked up speed and ignored the "stop"
order issued by the chasing police, said Zakaria who ordered his
men to fire the tear gas after a 45-minute chase.
</P>
<P>
The police found about 100 kilograms of fish in the hold of
the 17-meter-long vessel, which is equipped with sophisticated
gadgets including radar and echo sounder. The vessel was later
escorted to a Marine Police base in Langkawi, and the 36-year-old
skipper and his 22 crew members, aged between 16 and 45, were
handed over to the Fisheries Department, Zakaria said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
