<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illiteracy Eradication Drive in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region
has been commended by UNESCO for its achievements in eliminating
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
When New China was founded in 1949, more than 90 percent of the
region's population was illiterate. In spite of the progress since
then, people above the age of 15 who could not read or write
accounted for 22 percent of the region's population in 1990.
</P>
<P>
To stamp out illiteracy and improve local people's lives, the
regional government created a program on illiteracy eradication in
1991, which stipulated that nearly all the young and middle-aged
people in the countryside should be given the opportunity to learn
to read and write by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the financially-pinched regional
government has poured more than 16.8 million yuan into the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Mass media, women's federations, science workers, and even some
religion workers have helped with the work.
</P>
<P>
According to the regional education department, 234,000 farmers
have learned to read and write, and the rate of the illiterates
over 15 years of age has dropped to 10.54 percent. The per capita
income for farmers increased from 594 yuan in 1990 to 1,037 yuan
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
