<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan, Uganda, Iran Reach Formula for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Sudan, Uganda and Iran today
reached a formula to settle border disputes between Khartoum and
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a press conference after an agreement was
initialed here by the Sudanese Presidential Advisor Ahmad Mahmoud
Alasi, the Ugandan Foreign Ministry Director General James
Baba, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Hussein Sheikholeslan and
a senior Malawian official.
</P>
<P>
The four sides agreed the peace accord will be officially
signed by the foreign ministers of Sudan, Uganda and Iran
sometime in December.
</P>
<P>
Malawi was involved as observer and Iran mediator.
</P>
<P>
The three countries as well as Malawi have agreed to form two
teams of political and military specialists, one in Khartoum and
the other in Kampala to inspect and observe the situation in the
Sudan-Uganda border regions.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said at the press
conference that the specialists will keep the parties concerned
informed of what was happening in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the four countries met here today to follow
up the Khartoum agreement signed by Sudan and Uganda on
normalizing relations through mediation efforts by Iranian
President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani who made a tour of Sudan and
some other African countries in September.
</P>
<P>
While answering a question raised by Xinhua, Velayati said that
the new agreement will be officially signed individually or
collectively in December.
</P>
<P>
Both the Sudanese and Ugandan representatives pledged that they
would commit themselves to the agreement, while expressing their
thanks to the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese presidential advisor reaffirmed his government's
support for the peace endeavor, noting "There is no substitute
for peace."
</P>
<P>
"We have long-time relations with sisterly Uganda and there is a
special emphasis on peaceful co-existence with the neighbor in
our history and tradition," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "you can not choose your mother, but you have
to live with your neighbor."
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Foreign Ministry director general said, "This is
a very important journey for peace. We would like to thank all
the parties that have helped us in this journey."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the support of his government for the
peace and security with its neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said: "The Tehran meeting was a very important
and valuable step toward the implementation of Khartoum agreement
which has been valued by the heads of the four states that
could bring us closer (to) establishment of peace and stability
between the two countries (Sudan and Uganda)."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran finds itself duty-bound to continue
efforts and has used its good offices at international arenas
to bring about peace and international security and to this
end, it has been the initiator of mediation at some stages.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to give more details about the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reportedly to involve the pullout of Sudanese
rebel forces from a 100-kilometer-wide zone from either side of
the Sudanese-Ugandan border.
</P>
<P>
Uganda broke diplomatic relations with Sudan on April 24,
1995.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Uganda have exchanged accusations of each other of
backing respective rebel groups in their border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
