<HEADLINE> China's Eximbank Guarantees Syndicated Loan for Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of
China has offered guarantees for a syndicated loan of 103 million
US dollars to finance the building and export of six vessels to
Malaysia, according to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The money, arranged by a syndicate of 14 banks led by Japan's
Sumitomo Bank and Sanwa Bank in the form of structural trade
financing, will be used by China Shipbuilding Trading Co. and the
Jiangnan, Hudong and Dalian shipyards to build for and export to
Malaysia four bulk carriers and two chemical products
carriers. The six ships have a combined tonnage of 329,000
dead-weight tons and a contracted value of 184 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the Eximbank has guaranteed a large-sum
syndicated loan for the export of Chinese vessels. The first loan
was issued last year by the Royal Bank of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since it went into operation in July of
1994, the Chinese bank has raised a total of 7.78 billion yuan and
185 million US dollars for the country's exports of oil tankers,
liquefied gas carriers, container ships, bulk carriers, chemical
products carriers, barges, and multi-purpose vessels.
</P>
<P>
The 238 vessels exported with the aid of Eximbank have a
combined tonnage of 4.173 million dead-weight tons and a
contracted value of 3.12 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Eximbank's board chairman Tong Zhiguang said that his
two-year-old policy bank will continue to consolidate cooperation
with the international financial community in an effort to boost
China's export of vessels.
</P>
<P>
Eximbank is one of China's three policy-oriented banks designed
to provide financial backing for China's exports of capital goods
including machinery, electronic products and complete sets of
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
