<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Completes Assessment of State Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China has completed 1995's annual
assessment of how the value of state property in state-owned
enterprises has been maintained and increased, the State
Administration of State Property (SASP) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 83,315 large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises
had been examined by the end of July, including 4,326 companies
run by the central authorities, and 78,989 local firms.
</P>
<P>
An initial analysis shows that the account value of the
state-owned rights and interests of the assessed enterprises was
74 percent of the total amount of all state-owned enterprises at
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of state-owned assets in the examined enterprises grew
by 3.59 percent in 1995, 0.59 percent higher than the target set
at the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
The analysis shows that 84 percent of the added value was
reported in enterprises run by the central authorities, and the
value of state property appreciated most in the sectors of
automobile, post and telecommunications, tobacco, petrochemicals,
power and petroleum.
</P>
<P>
It also shows that the coastal areas and new industrial centers
outperformed the interior areas and old industrial bases in
maintaining and increasing the value of state property.
</P>
<P>
An official at the SASP said that the overall operation of
state-owned property was not satisfactory, as the 3.59 percent
growth rate for the value of state property was far lower than
the interest rates for bank deposits during the same period.
</P>
<P>
A high asset-to-liability ratio and a high ratio of bad assets
are two major elements behind the poor performance of state
property, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors include a lack of liquidity of available assets,
disorder in the management of investments and inadequate measures
to reduce losses, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
