<HEADLINE> Zambia's Electoral Commission Bill To Be Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper today quoted Vice President Godfrey
Miyanda as saying that the provision to include one
from the ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD) and another
from the opposition will be withdrawn because the government has
realized that it will make the commission partisan.
</P>
<P>
Backbenchers especially from the ruling party earlier attacked the
provision saying it will create confusion and adversely affect the
independence of the commission.
</P>
<P>
According to the electoral commission bill, the commission should
consist of a chairperson and four members, one representing the
ruling party and another the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The members' appointment will be made by President Frederick
Chiluba and the chairperson should have held high judicial office
while members must have experience on electoral matters.
</P>
<P>
Backbenchers of the biggest opposition United National
Independence Party (UNIP) said that the president should not appoint
the commissioners and suggested that each party selects one
representative.
</P>
<P>
MMD members said that there will be nothing wrong in allowing the
head of state to appointe the commissioners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
