<HEADLINE> 13 African States Launch Anti-Money laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen southern and
eastern African countries have pledged closer co-operation and
tighter legislation to combat money laundering in the region.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from southern and eastern states ended a three-day
conference on money laundering yesterday in Cape Town which was
sponsored by the Commonwealth Secretaariat and the
Inter-governmental Financial Action Task Force(FATF), said a
statement issued today to the press.
</P>
<P>
The delegates agreed that there is an urgent need for the
countries to implement anti-money laundering laws, based on FATF
recommendations and model laws drawn up by the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
They said the approach to prevent disguise of the origin of
proceeds from illegal activities should be a broad-based one,
incorporating government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
To this end, a national co-ordinating group on anti-money
laundering matters should be established for each country.
</P>
<P>
The delegates noted that the establishment of a regional
mechanism to co-ordinate efforts against money laundering,known
as the Southern and Eastern African Financial Action Task Force,
is seen as necessary.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Botswana,Kenya,Lesotho,Malawi,Mozambique,
Namibia,Mauritius,Swaziland,South Africa,Tanzania,Uganda,Zambia
and Zimbabwe attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The FATF is an inter-governmental body formed to develop and
promote polices to combat money launderirng. Its member- ship
comprises 26 countries and the European Commission and the Gulf
Co-operation Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
