<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Military On Recapturing Kilinochchi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Sri Lankan military
officer revealed here today that the government troops had met
with very stiff resistance from the rebels in recapturing the
strategic Kilinochchi town which straddles the A-9 Highway from
Colombo to Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister General G.A. Ratwatte said at a press
conference here this afternoon that the liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) rebels in Kilinochchi town fought very hard in a vain
attempt to prevent the troops from capturing the town, which they
were using as a hub on the northern mainland.
</P>
<P>
Kilinochchi town was a center for the LTTE as it had a
hospital, weapon factories, communication center and several other
important installations.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE had rushed in reinforcements from other areas and a
large number of them had been killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
General Ratwatte said everything had gone according to plan and
that they had planned to take Kilinochchi town in a 7-day battle.
The troops spent only one day more.
</P>
<P>
Now, that Kilinochchi town had been liberated, he said, the
rebels took to the jungles and the troops would relentlessly
pursue them until they are defeated.
</P>
<P>
He said 250 soldiers were killed in the fighting while an
estimated 500 rebels had been killed and another 1,000 injured.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question, he said the government was willing
to negotiate with the LTTE either directly or through a mediator
only if they meet the conditions laid down by the government --
laying down their arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
