<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges China to Reform Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The time is ripe for China to
establish a unified pension system, the World Bank says in a new
report.
</P>
<P>
"China now has a golden opportunity to move toward a unified
pension system that combines defined benefits with funded
individual accounts," according to the report, which was drafted
with support from the State Planning Commission and the Ministry
of Labor.
</P>
<P>
China's existing pension system has two big problems: the
immediate hardship of the pension burden of state-owned
enterprises and the long-term troubles arising from the aging
population, the report says.
</P>
<P>
"The problem of state-owned enterprises is not due to the
overall demographic dependency ratio, which is still low, but to
the fragmentation of the system, generous benefit rates, and a
high rate of exemptions and noncompliance stemming from the high
contribution rates," it says.
</P>
<P>
The long-term problem stems from the aging of the population
combined with incomplete pension coverage, the report says, noting
that the solution lies in expanding coverage and creating a
multi-layered system that combines mandatory social pooling with
mandatory individual accounts and a social insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
The current pension system fails to contribute to economic
development, as it does not encourage labor mobility, provide a
level playing field for different enterprises, expedite
state-owned enterprise restructuring by de-linking pension
provision from enterprise management, nor assist in the term
transformation of savings and the funding of infrastructure and
other long-term investments, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It argues that when compared with other countries, China's
costs of transition are lower and its capacity to bear these costs
is greater.
</P>
<P>
The report identifies four factors that facilitate financing of
the transition in China: the unification of the pension system,
the structural change in the economy, rapid growth of the gross
domestic product and the capital gains in state assets.
</P>
<P>
"These favorable factors will generate resources that will
enable China to pay its obligations to pensioners and workers
under the old system, while making a transition to a new reformed
system," the report says.
</P>
<P>
The formal pension system in China is a pay-as-you-go defined
benefit system that covers mainly the state sector in urban areas,
it adds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
