<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Declines in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The crime rate in Hong Kong is
declining and the rate is considerably lower than that in London,
New York or Tokyo, according to a Hong Kong government official.
</P>
<P>
At a function held here today, Secretary for Security Peter Lai
said that during the first eight months of this year, Hong Kong's
overall crime rate dropped 13.7 percent compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the total number of reported crimes in the period
decreased 11.5 percent, and the total number of violent crimes
dropped 11.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the crimes committed by illegal immigrants (IIs), he said,
the situation was not as serious as some sensational reports
resulting from a number of high profile cases would have it.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the first six months of this year, when
compared with the same period last year, the number of IIs
involved in all crimes decreased from 2,213 in 1995 and from 2,519
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In the period, the number of IIs arrested for crimes was 748, a
decrease of 37 percent when compared with the same period in 1995,
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Vietnamese migrants (VMs) issue, Lai said that over
9,000 VMs had been repatriated to Vietnam this year, as compared
with 2,600 in the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
As of today, there are about 12,000 VMs in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
From October onwards, he said, the Hong Kong government will
progressively step up the pace of the Orderly Repatriation
Program, from the current rate of 600 to 700 per month to about
1,000 per month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
