<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Monetary Authority Opens New York Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) opened its first overseas office in New York
today, as a step to enhance the region's de facto central bank's
presence in the international financial community.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the HKMA, said at the opening
ceremony: "This office will enable us to ensure that our fingers
are kept on the pulse of the market so as to facilitate the
professional performance of our function as a full-fledged
monetary authority."
</P>
<P>
One of the main tasks of the office is to monitor the foreign
exchange and the US fixed income markets in the New York time
zone. This function, as the chief executive put it, will help the
HKMA to manage its substantial reserves prudently and profitably.
Hong Kong boasts 59.1 billion US dollars worth of foreign exchange
reserves, one of the highest among Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
The office will also strengthen ties with the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York and other American regulatory authorities, added
Yam.  
</P>
