<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Inflation Rate Hits 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's inflation rate as
measured by consumer prices increased 4.7 percent as of the end of
last month, surpassing the government-set control target for the
entire year of 4.5 percent, the Ministry of Finance and Economy
said today.
</P>
<P>
In September alone, inflation rate rose 0.3 percent, bringing
the nine-month total to 4.7 percent, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
With the prices of gasoline and other oil products increasing
by an average of 2.04 percent this month, inflation rate will
continue to increase for the remainder of the year, a ministry
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the inflation rate exceeded the price control target
for the year as of the end of September, a bumper harvest is
expected to contribute to comparatively stable prices," the
official noted.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue its price stabilization efforts
during the rest of the year, one of which calls for aggressively
inducing the lowering of manufactured commodity prices, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
