<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Progress in Administrative Reform Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has made progress in its
administrative reform process, a senior vietnamese official said
today.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of 1995, the government's structure has been scaled
down from 27 ministries to 22, from more than 30 professional
offices to about 20 at the provincial level and from 20 to 10
offices at the district level," said cabinet minister Phan Ngoc
Tuong, head of the government's organizing committee, who is also
chief of the steering committee of an administrative reform
program funded by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The ministries and offices have also begun simplifying
administrative procedures in a number of sectors that have direct
impact on foreign investment, production and business licensing,
land management and other essential areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Two new ordinances adopted by the national assembly -- the
country's congress -- have been promulgated to clarify the
authority and liability of the national assembly, the government,
the people's council and the people's committee at all levels,
Tuong said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 10,000 government employees have been
trained at administrative schools over the past two years, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
