<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Stations in Riyadh Close Down Amid Price War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A savage price war that
broke out in Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia, among gasoline
stations has caused several stations to close down, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the biggest oil producing country in the world,
and gasoline prices there are lower than in every other country
except Iraq. But some gasoline stations in Riyadh sell 53 halalas
(0.14 U.S. dollar) a liter, seven halalas less than the regular
price of 60 halalas (0.16 dollar), forcing five gasoline stations
in the capital to close down for failure to match the
lower-than-cost prices.
</P>
<P>
Despite official warnings from the government, the price war is
still very much felt in the capital, with many of the gas station
owners aggressively promoting their slashed prices, according to
Saudi English-language daily Arab News.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have asked them to stick to the recommended
price of 60 halalas per liter, but they have failed to heed the
call.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad Ibrahim, manager of a gas station, was quoted as
saying that too much investment in this sector has led to the
over-proliferation of gasoline stations, each trying to lure as
many customers as they can.
</P>
<P>
Another gas station manager Siraji Muhammad said that he was
on the verge of going out of business because the competition was
so fierce.
</P>
<P>
All gasoline stations in Saudi Arabia are privately owned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Palestinians: Do Not Lose Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has appealed to Palestinians not to lose hope
for peace talks, saying the Washington summit was a chance for a
"fresh start" on peace.
</P>
<P>
"I ask you, don't go into mourning, don't lose hope,"
Netanyahu said in an address to Palestinians on Israel
Television Thursday night. "This is an opportunity for a fresh
start for the peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu appealed to the Palestinians to remain calm and have
faith in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, scheduled to
resume on Sunday at the Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
"There are no winners and no losers if we fight each other,"
said the Israeli premier. "If we fight each other and if we
return to bloody riots, we will both be losers. If we walk
together on the process of peace, we will both be winners."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior U.S. official said that Netanyahu has
assured Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
during their meetings in Washington that he intends to complete
the Erez negotiations within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu returned to Israel Thursday, one day after
the Washington summit, which was called to resuscitate the peace
process following last week's violent clashes in the West Bank,
Gaza and Jerusalem, ended with no significant results.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli and Palestinian sides agreed at the summit
to hold continuous talks at the Erez checkpoint, which would focus
on security issues and the Israeli army's redeployment in the West
Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In a phone conversation on Thursday night, the prime minister
reportedly told Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak that if the
Palestinians take what he termed as a practical approach, he has
no doubt that Sunday's negotiations will be productive.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is scheduled today to report to the Knesset
(Israel's parliament) and the cabinet about the summit at
special sessions, after he briefed President Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister's office is preparing for the
talks at the Erez checkpoint, but it has not yet been decided if
Netanyahu and Arafat will participate in the first meeting
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
