<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Co-operation Overseas In The Law Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China intends to continue
letting foreign law firms open offices in China, and to encourage
Chinese law firms to establish offices abroad, Vice-Minister of
Justice Zhang Geng said here today.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1992, when China began letting overseas law firms
practice law in China, a total of 73 offices have been approved
through a strict process in the cities of Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Haikou, and Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
Co-operation has been good, and China plans to expand exchanges
with overseas lawyers on the basis of the past few years'
experience, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The co-operation has played a vital role in China's legal
development and improving China's investment environment, and has
helped Chinese lawyers learn directly from their overseas
counterparts, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jisheng, the president of the All-China Lawyers'
Association, says that, since 1986, the association has
established broad contacts with lawyers' associations in more than
30 countries and regions that have involved official visits,
information exchanges, and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the association has reached agreements with the
judiciary in Canada, Britain, Hong Kong and Singapore, on training
lawyers for China. More than 80 Chinese lawyers have received
training in Britain, and Chinese law firms have set up seven
offices in the Unites States, Singapore, and Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Red Tide" Contaminates Shellfish off Sabah, Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A "red tide" occurrence in
the waters off the west coast of Sabah, Malaysia, has contaminated
shelled molluscs which the public has been warned against eating.
</P>
<P>
The "red tide" phenomenon, a seasonal occurrence peculiar to
the sea in Sabah's west coast, is caused by the rapid growth of
planktons which turn the sea surface a reddish color and sea
creatures which consume the planktons produce a toxin which can
kill consumers, an official statement said today.
</P>
<P>
The molluscs, especially bivalves like oyster and cockle, from
the affected areas, should not be sold or eaten, Health Services
Department Deputy Director R. Meganathan warned in the statement.
</P>
<P>
He said fishes, prawns and crabs are safe to eat, but should be
thoroughly cleaned before cooking.
</P>
<P>
Meganathan said his department and the Fisheries Department are
monitoring the situation, and the public would be informed of new
developments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
