<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Phones Mubarak To Mend Fence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Prime minister telephoned
Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak last night apparently in a bid
to patch the strained relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who returned from Washington summit Thursday
afternoon, briefed the Egyptian president on the results of the
summit held on October 1-2, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak, a principal Middle East peace broker,
declined an invitation by President Bill Clinton to attend the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's decision to stay away from the meeting appeared to
be a further indication of the tense relations between Egypt and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
When asked to explain his absence, Mubarak replied: "Our
absence does give an indication that we are not pleased with the
situation and obstinate acts of Israel concerning the
Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
On several occasions in recent weeks, Mubarak could hardly
hide his anger at Netanyahu's inaction in the peace process
despite his promise made during his Cairo visit after rise to
power in June.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that it was a pity that Mubarak did not
participate in the summit, stressing that it is important that
they maintain contacts.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu promised to Mubarak that he plans to ease the
closure on the Palestinian territories. He added that if the
Palestinians adopt a serious approach progress is certain in the
new round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the Washington summit, the Joint Israeli-Palestinian
Steering Committee is due to meet at Erez on Sunday to discuss,
among other issues, the long-delayed Hebron redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he would support any progress in the Middle
East peace process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
