<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Ping-Pong Coach Convicted of Spying for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli citizen has
been held on charges of spying for the former Soviet Union
in the 1980s, reported Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Radlies, who is an engineer living in Ramat Gan,
a satellite city of Tel Aviv, served as a coach of the
Israeli national table tennis team before he was arrested three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
He was apprehended for spying for Moscow for seven years. Police
confiscated some spy equipments from his home.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Radlies was suspected of sending coded
documents and information to KGB, the State Security Committee
of the former Soviet Union, from his Ramat Gan apartment.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, he reported to KGB on his reserve
duties with the army, tension along the Israeli northern border
and political situation in the Jewish state. He also traveled
abroad to meet his KGB handler, said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Radlies had received special underground espionage training
before being sent from Moscow to Israel in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
