<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five More Die of Dengue Fever in Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- At least five more people died
of dengue fever in the Indian capital of New Delhi in the past 48
hours and 62 more were taken to hospitals in the city, the Times
of India said today.
</P>
<P>
The toll rose to 60 with children the main victims. A total of
912 persons are reported to have suffered dengue fever since the
disease outbreak came to light three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Of the 194 people admitted with dengue fever to All India
Institute of Medical Sciences, the most famous hospital in the
capital, 22 have died. Cases have been reported from almost every
part of the city.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever is a mosquito-transmitted disease. The patient
suffers from sustained high fever accompanied by severe ache in
the head, eyes, muscles and joints.
</P>
<P>
Its worse form, dengue hemorrhage fever, which is usually
fatal, is identified from pimple-like red spots all over the body,
bleeding nose and gums.
</P>
<P>
Medical scientists here urged the government to install a test
laboratory in Delhi for the detection and confirmation of the
dengue virus.
</P>
<P>
They complained that even though the first known death because
of dengue hemorrhage fever took place in the institute of medical
sciences on August 22, a laboratory which can confirm dengue virus
is still not available in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU States, Major Importers of Tanzanian Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
member states have been major importers of Tanzanian coffee, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics issued recently by the Tanzania Coffee
Board (TCB), EU countries imported between January and June
this year 43.29 percent of Tanzanian coffee
estimated at 20,698,083 kilograms worth 45.2 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The leading importers in order of the volume of purchases are
Germany, The Netherlands, France, Belgium, United Kingdom, Demark and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Germany, the main EU importer of Tanzanian coffee, purchased
5.4 million kilograms during the period, valued at 12 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that Japan is the leading importer
outside the EU, having imported Tanzanian coffee worth 22.5 million U.S.
Dollars, or 19 percent of the country's total coffee exports between
January and June this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
