<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The bank of Credit Lyonnais is going out of deficit after
years of losing money, as it is benefiting from a relentless
salvage program by the state.
</P>
<P>
The bank benefited from 67 million francs (13.4 million
U.S. dollars) of state aid in the first six months of 1996 alone.
The overall aid to save the bank is expected to attain 100 billion
francs (20 billion U.S. dollars), which is equal to the cost of
the tunnel under the English Channel, the state debt of Algeria,
10 times as much as the international aid to Palestine, 30 times
as much as the cost of the Bastille Opera House in Paris, and four
times as much as the cost of Disneyland Paris.
</P>
<P>
-- The Taliban has cut sound and image in the Afghan capital.
The Afghan women are again obliged to wear strict chador. Men and
women are separated on buses in Kabul. The leader of Taliban,
Mollah Mohammed Omar, has ordered the people of Kabul not to leave
the city.
</P>
<P>
The Amnesty International said that the students have imposed a
rule of terror in Kabul by throwing nearly 1,000 people into jail
and destroying everything they considered as "non-Islamic," such
as tape recorders, cassettes, magazines and toys. With the
imposition of the Sharia, Taliban suggests that photographers and
journalists quit their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The plan to reform the social security system by the French
government has caused an open confrontation with the doctors.
Three major trade unions of doctors decided on Thursday to stage a
strike on October 17, following a strike by night-time doctors
last evening.
</P>
<P>
-- As the French-Italian summit started in Naples last evening,
the Italian lire rose to its highest point against the franc and
German mark, with 1,000 lires against 3.412 francs and 1.006
marks. Meanwhile, Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro told
Chirac that the "history of our two countries goes much further
than the fleeting quarrels." 
</P>
