<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Praised for Reconciliation Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has impressively upheld
its policy of reconciliation since independence in 1980, visiting
former British Minister of African Affairs Richard Luce said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richard Luce, who helped negotiate the end of Zimbabwe's war
of liberation, said he is particularly glad to find Zimbabwe is
one of the few which retained many whites after independence.
</P>
<P>
''It is very impressive that 80,000 whites are still working
here. At independence there were just over 200,000. In some
countries all of them could have left by now, for one reason or
another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Luce is in Zimbabwe as Chairman of the Commonwealth
Foundation, to present prizes in Harare on Friday to the best
Commonwealth novelists.
</P>
<P>
''I think it is very impressive that the government of
President Mugabe followed the constitutional arrangements agreed
to in Britain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Luce also noted evidences of strong economic activities, adding
that he sees more new buildings and offices in the capital
of Harere than the last time he visited Zimbabwe in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
