<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Farmers Get Better Jobs Through Youth League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Young farmer Hao Haiping is
satisfied. Earning more than 1,000 yuan (120 Us dollars) a month
makes him a member of Beijing's middle income population.
</P>
<P>
Many of Hao's friends from the poor Xiyang County of Shanxi
Province came to suburban Shunyi County seeking higher income and
better professional skills.
</P>
<P>
Xiyang, best known for Dazhai, a village established as a model
for the whole country during the "cultural revolution", has sent
840 people to Shunyi during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
They have mailed more than one million yuan (120,000 US
dollars) in savings each year and greatly helped the economy of
their home county.
</P>
<P>
These young people moved to beijing under the organization of
local branches of the Chinese Communist Youth League in Xiyang and
Shunyi, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Leagues in the two counties have signed contracts, in which
Shunyi provides jobs in its rapidly developing township
enterprises and Xiyang is responsible for recruiting employees.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1993, the league helped 25 counties in the
booming coastal Shandong, Jiangsu, Zhejiang and Fujian provinces
reach labor export agreements with 25 poor inland counterparts.
</P>
<P>
With the help of youth leagues, a total of 150,000 young
farmers found jobs in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 170 counties have established similar
relationships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
