<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Production at Jungar Opencut Coal Mine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The second of three projects at
an opencut mine and auxiliary coal dressing plant in the Jungar
Coalfield, in Inner Mongolia, began trial production in late
September.
</P>
<P>
The Jungar Coalfield is one of China's strategic construction
projects for shifting energy development to western areas.
</P>
<P>
The Heidaigou Mine, which has an annual production capacity of
12 million tons of coal and has a coal dressing plant, is the
first large opencut mine developed by China.
</P>
<P>
According to Song Hanfeng, general manager of the Jungar Coal
Industrial Corporation, some 7.85 billion yuan of investment had
been used by the end of August for the first phase of construction.
</P>
<P>
Other projects have included a 200,000 kw power plant that has
been completed and was linked to a local power grid three years
ago, generating 3.08 billion kwh of electricity, and a 264-km
electrified railway for use in the coalfield, that is the first
electric railway line in Inner Mongolia. It will operate from
Datong in Shanxi Province to Jungar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Call For Improvement Of Children's Situation In China's Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior official has said that
a greater effort should be made in improving children's situation
in poverty-stricken areas in west China, although marked progress
has been already made.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate for infants and children under five and for
pregnant women in the poor areas is much higher than the national
average, Xu Zhijian, deputy director of the Women and Children's
Working Committee of the State Council, told a press conference
last week.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a considerable number of children are dropping out
of school, he said, and something must be done for these children.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the Chinese government has been carrying out
the principles of a summit conference on the world's children, and
on protecting the Chinese children's rights and on improving the
country's legal system, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have also been made to provide funds in the last
several years for this purpose, and most indices for children's
lives in the poor areas have been met, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the mortality rate for infants and children under five
in China was 36.4 per thousand and 44.5 per thousand, a 27-percent
decrease for both figures compared with 1991, while the death
rate of pregnant women was 61.9 per 100,000, a decrease of 36.4
percent from 1990's figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
