<HEADLINE> India's Export Growth Slumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Adding fuels to fears about an
economic slowdown, India's exports have slid into single digit
growth.
</P>
<P>
According to official data available here today, the exports
during April-August of 1996 was 13.5 billion US dollars as against
12.3 billion US dollars during the corresponding period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Exports during August 1996 indicated a gloomier picture with a
growth of just 2.38 percent as compared to August 1995.
</P>
<P>
Exports during August 1996 was estimated at 2.6 billion dollars
as against 2.54 billion US dollars for the same month of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Commerce Ministry has tried to explain the slump in
export growth by saying that global exports are expected to
increase by only 5 percent as compared to 7.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
A substantial slowdown in exports has also occurred in other
regions including Southeast Asia, a press release issued by the
ministry has said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
