<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Complain Against Indonesia's "National Car" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan may file a complaint with
the World Trade Organization (WTO) later today against Indonesia's
"national car" policy, Japan's International Trade and Industry
Minister Shumpei Tsukahara said today.
</P>
<P>
The complaint isdue to be filed on Friday morning local time in
Geneva, where the WTO headquarters is located.
</P>
<P>
Under Jakarta's car policy, domestically-owned automakers can
enjoy tariff and luxury sales tax exemptions on condition that
they boost the locally-made content ratio to 60 percent in three
years.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture between PT Timor Putra Nasional of Indonesia,
controlled by President Suahrto's youngest son, and Kia Motors of
South Korea is the only company that enjoys this status.
</P>
<P>
The venture is allowed to assemble its Timor cars at Kia plants
and export them to Indonesia duty-free for one year until its
local plants are ready.
</P>
<P>
Japan argues that the policy violates the WTO's most favored
nation status and national treatment principles by favoring South
Korean cars, and contravenes the Trade-Related Investment Measures
accord by linking tax privileges to local content requirements.
</P>
<P>
"It is truly regrettable that things have ended up this way"
said Tuskahara.
</P>
<P>
However, the issue "should never adversely affect the friendly
relationship between Japan and Indonesia that has been developed
over many years", he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Contribute to New IMF Emergency Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai central bank is seeking
an government approval to contribute funds to a new emergency
facility for the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to help boost
the country's image in the world.
</P>
<P>
Kleo-Thong Haetrakul, director of the economic research
department of the Bank of Thailand, Thursday said that the bank
has received an invitation to join the new arrangement to borrow
(NAB).
</P>
<P>
The IMF selected members for the facility based on a country's
general economic strength, including economic growth, balance of
payment and official foreign exchange reserves, the official was
quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is expected to set aside 1 percent of its total
reserves worth 49 billion US dollars for the IMF emergency cash
facility, Kleo-Thong said.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the NAB, which can be tapped by developing
countries to tackle sudden financial crises, will also give
Thailand protection in the world financial system, Kleo-Thong
said.
</P>
<P>
The facility will be used as a tool to ease any possible
economic volatility in the future and give Thailand an opportunity
to borrow funds at a low cost, she said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a number of countries from Asia and Europe,
including Australia, Austria, Denmark, South Korea, Malaysia,
Singapore, Spain, Finland, Norway, and Luxembourg, have agreed to
join the NAB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
