<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Agribusiness Exports Develop Quickly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's agricultural and
livestock sector is now one of the country's most important
sources of hard currency as mechanization and more professional
marketing have paid off.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the sector brought in 4 billion dollars in export
earnings, up 50 percent on 1994. With exports reaching 2.718
billion dollars in the first eight months of this year, official
estimates put the total for 1996 at some 5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural food sector registered a 764-million-dollar
trade surplus last year, a situation not seen since 1987.
</P>
<P>
The main Mexican agricultural and livestock exports are coffee,
legumes, vegetables, tomatoes, beef, shrimps, fruit, fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 percent of the 20 million hectares of arable land
under cultivation is given over to growing fruit, vegetables, and
flowers.
</P>
<P>
Mexico will export 800,000 tons of horticultural and fruit
products in 1996 worth 600 million dollars, 200 million dollars
more than that of 1995, according to the National Confederation
of Horticulturists.
</P>
<P>
Bananas account for 45 percent of the volume of exported fruit,
followed by lemons with 21.3 percent and mangoes with 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Mexico says tomatoes, of which 465,000 tons were
exported in 1995 worth 585.6 million dollars, was the third
biggest hard currency earner in the agricultural and livestock
sector.
</P>
<P>
Economists here attributed the rapid growth in exports of the
agricultural and livestock sector to government support in
production and the establishment of a new marketing system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Agribusiness Exports Develop Quickly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Mexican government has launched a number of programs to
promote the production and marketing of agricultural products
over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
It adopted a program to provide rural farmers with additional
financial aid to promote production and marketing during 1993 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Support and Services for the Marketing of
Agricultural and Livestock Products (Aserca), a branch of the
Agriculture Ministry, has provided support for vegetable, fruit
and flower producers.
</P>
<P>
It has also assisted other agricultural and livestock producers
by providing them with materials, machinery, equipment and
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have been helped to create necessary infrastructure for
regional collection, selection, packaging, storage, transportation
and marketing. Aserca also organized producers into marketing
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In another program, called the System of Commercial Linking for
the Agricultural and Livestock Sector (Secsa), the government
promoted the creation of a direct sales system. It eliminated the
need for middlemen so that most of the profits went to the
producers.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Foreign Trade has also granted producers and
exporters credits at preferential rates to promote the export of
farm products.
</P>
<P>
However, the sector still has many problems, among them an
obsolete and impractical production model and a lack of
organization, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Because of excessive dependence on the U.S. market, Mexico's
agricultural and livestock products for export now face a new
challenge amid increasing trade disputes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Experts have proposed that Mexico diversify its product base
and exploit the potential of its other resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Adjourns Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate formally
adjourned on Thursday after passing an aviation bill and major
federal parks legislation.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives, whose members have already left
to concentrate on the election campaign, will follow suit on
Friday. That will bring to a close the 104th Congress, the first
run by Republicans in more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
"We got it done," Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said before
officially declaring the session over. "I believe that the entire
membership of the 104th Congress can leave today proud of their
accomplishments."
</P>
<P>
The 92-2 vote to approve the Federal Aviation Administration
bill, and voice vote on a parks bill to expand and improve more
than 100 sites in 41 states, cleared the last hurdles to ending
the first Republican-led Congress in four decades.
</P>
<P>
After moving on the parks bill, Lott and Democratic leader Tom
Daschle made a ceremonial phone call from Lott's office to
President Bill Clinton to announce that this session of Congress
had concluded its business.
</P>
<P>
The House for the most part finished its work last Saturday,
when it passed a 1997 spending bill. But it scheduled a session
for Friday afternoon, just in case action had been needed on
measures the Senate was to pass at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, whose administration has expressed
opposition to the Federal Express clause, nevertheless welcomed
the FAA bill's passage Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Because of this legislation, criminal background checks can
now be conducted on airport personnel, new explosives detection
technology can be deployed, baggage will be checked in more
thoroughly, passenger profiling will be instituted and families
who lose a loved one in an accident will be able to get the help
that they need," Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Congress has seen some major accomplishments:
telecommunications, farm support and welfare overhauls, and the
disastrous showdown over a balanced budget deal that resulted in
two partial government shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
Wishing to avoid such a debacle this year, the House on
Saturday and the Senate on Monday approved a 389 billion dollar
spending bill for the fiscal year that began Tuesday. The measure,
which included an extra 6.5 billion dollars sought by the
administration for education and other social programs, provided
funds for all the federal departments and agencies not covered by
previously approved spending bills.
</P>
<P>
It contained none of the "killer" provisions that had prompted
President Clinton to veto spending bills last year.
</P>
<P>
Lott said it was a historic Congress, with major achievements
in welfare, health insurance and illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also welcomed one of the last pieces of
legislation to reach the Senate floor: a major federal parks bill
that initiates land exchanges, boundary changes and new
designations in 41 states.
</P>
<P>
The FAA bill includes 19 billion dollars over two years for
airport programs, including 4.6 billion dollars for new airport
grants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
