<HEADLINE> Nepali Upper House Members Protest Discrimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Legislators of the National
Assembly, the upper house of the Nepali parliament, Thursday
boycotted the house meeting for one hour in protest of the
government's discrimination in selecting members of a delegation
to the United Nations, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
The MPs said that the dignity and prestige of the upper house
had been affected as the Nepali team to the 51st UN general
assembly includes lawmakers only from the lower house, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
They accused the government of attempting to minimize the upper
house's role in the parliament and said the move by the government
had shown disrespect to the members of the house.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Nepali delegation to the UN general assembly, led
by Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani, is expected to leave
for new York later today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry sources, on condition of anonymity, said that
it took much longer time than expected for the ministry to
finalize the formation of the delegation to the UN general
assembly, which already began on September 17.  
</P>
</TEXT>
