<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa Hosts World Mines Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 representatives
from 70 states, international agencies and non-governmental
organizations convened here today on the first day of the
International Strategy Conference on Anti-Personnel Mines.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, hosted by Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy, is designed "to galvanize and catalyse international
action to negotiate a global ban on anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that each year two to five million land mines
are planted around the world, and some 110 million buried in 70
countries as a result of various conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy told the participants that reducing the use of mines
and dealing with the destructive legacy of land mines are two
challenges which required urgent attention of the world.
</P>
<P>
To advance the work of de-mining in different parts of the
world, Axworthy said that Canada will be making additional
contributions, and will sponsoring a Canadian seminar on de-mining
technology and assistance to victims early next year.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the meeting, Canadian Defence Minister David
Collenette announced that his country will reduce its stockpile of
90,000 anti-personnel mines to encourage other countries to ban
them.
</P>
<P>
However, Collenette insisted that Canada will withhold the
destruction of 30,000 anti-personnel mines until an international
ban is in effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
