<HEADLINE> U.S. to Keep Troops in Bosnia Until Mid-March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States will keep
thousands of troops in Bosnia after NATO's 60,000-strong
international peacekeeping force withdraw from the country in
December, U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry said today.
</P>
<P>
Perry told a Congressional hearing that the U.S. plans to
dispatch a new force of 5,000 American troops to Bosnia to act as
a "covering force" to assist the withdrawal. They will stay until
mid-March 1997.
</P>
<P>
NATO forces, which were sent to war-torn Bosnia to oversee the
implementation of last December's Dayton peace accords, will leave
when their mandate ends on December 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
Gen. John Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, told the Senate Armed Services Committee today that 10,000
Army soldiers will still be in Bosnia as of December 20 and, by
February 1, the force will be 7,500, with the last of those troops
pulling out by mid-March.
</P>
<P>
U.S. lawmakers have criticized the plan, saying it did
not square with repeated Clinton administration commitments to
have U.S. troops out of Bosnia by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
But Perry and Shalikashvili defended the covering force, saying
it would be a routine force and not an opening to a follow-up
deployment.
</P>
<P>
Former Bosnia peace negotiator Richard Holbrooke said Tuesday
that NATO should maintain a peacekeeping force in Bosnia next
year. Otherwise, he warned, there would be a risk of new war
breaking out.
</P>
<P>
European countries with troops in the peacekeeping force are
also willing to keep their soldiers there but insist the United
States participate in any troop deployment.
</P>
<P>
However, the Clinton administration will probably not decide
before the presidential election in November whether to keep
U.S. troops in Bosnia on a longer-term basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
