<HEADLINE> Musiyaka Elected Vice Chairman of Ukraine's Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Soviet (parliament) of
Ukraine today elected legislator Viktor Musiyaka as its vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
Musiyaka was elected by a vote of 277 in favor and 55 against
in a third round of voting during a regular session of the Supreme
Soviet after other two candidates were disqualified during the
first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
Musiyaka was nominated as one of the candidates for the post
after ex-vice chairman Oleg Demin was named by Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma as chief executive of Kharkov region two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Demin resigned from his post in the Supreme Soviet as required
by Ukraine's constitution.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the parliament session, Musiyaka said that it
was imperative for Ukraine to make laws on the Supreme Soviet, the
cabinet, the government organs and the Presidency.
</P>
<P>
Musiyaka, 50, a professor with Kharkov State Law Institute, was
a member of the Commission of Legislative Policy and Judicial
Reform under the Supreme Soviet. He once acted as President
Kuchma's representative in the Supreme Soviet in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
