<HEADLINE> Aviation Safety Worries Chile After Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister Jose
Miguel Insulza said here this morning that "there should be more
concern about air safety," when deploring the plane crash on
Wednesday that killed all 70 persons aboard including 31 Chileans.
</P>
<P>
The Aeriperu Flight 603 en route from Lima to Santiago went
down early Wednesday morning shortly after it took off from Lima
international airport.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said, "Our aeronautics authorities needed an
investigation because of the number of Chileans involved."
</P>
<P>
Forty-six relatives and friends of the Chilean victims flew to
Lima to look for the bodies of their beloved and would hold
Christian funerals for the dead there.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the Forensic Medicine Institute and the Civil
Registration Service of Chile also went to Lima to assist Peruvian
forensic experts to identify the bodies.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Ambassador to Peru Carlos Martinez Sotomayor, who is in
Santiago to attend a meeting, said this morning before leaving for
Lima that he is returning to Lima to speed up the transportation
of the bodies of the victims.
</P>
<P>
This is the second air crash that killed Chileans in a little
more than seven months. In the first fatal accident, 42 Chileans
were killed in February when a Peruvian plane crashed in a
mountain near Arequipa city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
