<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Plans to Revamp Railway Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 4 (Xinhua)-- Sri Lanka has plans to revamp its
railway services with 89 million US dollars aid from Japan,
Germany and the Netherlands, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's railway services were neglected in the past 20
years and it has now become necessary to revamp the services to
provide a satisfactory customer service, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government has to subsidize the railway department to the
tune of 14 million annually.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that to meet the railways immediate needs the
government has allocated funds for the purchase of 12 main line
locomotives and 15 diesel power sets within the next two years at
a cost of 61 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's railway at present has only 20 power sets whereas
it had as many as 45 sets in the 1960's when the passenger volume
was much lower.
</P>
<P>
Considering the present need to serve 35,202 million annual
passenger kilometers the railway needs at least 60 power sets, the
sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Under the revamping program it is proposed to improve 293
kilometers of long railway track to enable the increase of the
running speed of trains to 100 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the government also has plans to build
an electrified railway system to ease traffic congestion in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
