<HEADLINE> Greater Fire-Consciousness in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- No major fires have occurred in
the Hinggan Mountains in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province
since May 6, 1987, when a big fire that hit the area, according
to local forestry sources.
</P>
<P>
Mohe County in the province was the victim of the fire which
claimed 211 lives and injured 246, a result from smaller fires
started by a forest worker's improper use of a machine and two
other workers who were smoking.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a memorial hall was built in the county to
increase people's fire consciousness, and May 6 was designated
"Fire Day" and May, "Fire Month". Classes on fire prevention have
also been held in primary and middle schools, and permanent fire
exits put in all residences.
</P>
<P>
A fire prevention network has been set up in the Greater
Hinggan Mountain area. It deals with fire monitoring, fire
control, fire shelters, telecommunications, rescue work, and
education and logistics systems.
</P>
<P>
The Greater Hinggan Forest area covers 8,369,076 hectares of
land in Heilongjiang Province and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region is one of the largest in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
