<HEADLINE> Oil Output Steady In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's oilfields plan
to annually produce 74 million tons of crude oil by the year 2000,
according to Zhang Hong, deputy general manager of China Oil and
Gas Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The northeast is China's leading oil producer and is where its
most famous oilfield, Daqing, is located, as are the Liaohe and
Jilin fields. Northeastern oilfields produced 74.93 million tons
of crude oil last year, accounting for a half of the nation's
total.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year-Plan period, oilfields there will
work on discovering more oil and gas and plan to get 86.3 billion
yuan from sales and to implement a strategy of stablizing oil
production in the east and exploring oil reserves in the west.
</P>
<P>
They will also make an effort to establish a modern enterprise
mechanism and gradually improve their assets responsibility system.
</P>
<P>
Geologists have discovered 7.686 billion tons of proven oil
reserves in the northeast, accounting for 44.1 percent of the
total oil potential in China, and 106.84 billion cu m of natural
gas reserves, or 7.6 percent of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
The northeast had produced 1.599 billion tons of crude by the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Daqing, China's largest oilfield, Last year produced 56 million
tons of crude oil and, according to officials, has mapped out a
plan for future development and will work harder to get 185.5
billion yuan in total output value, 46.2 billion yuan in profits,
and have 29.8 billion yuan in taxes by the year 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
