<HEADLINE> U.S. Aid to Combat Drugs in Colombia Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
cut aid to Colombia to fight drug trafficking by 90 percent over
the last four years, a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The "El Espectador" daily said the U.S. Congress approved a
package of 142 million U.S. dollars in 1992 to help Colombia in
its war against drugs, but that amount had fallen to just 10.6
million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year Colombia invested 985 million dollars to combat drug
trafficking, far from enough to wage the necessary full-scale war
on drugs, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Colombia plans to spend 31 million dollars in 1996 on the
"Alternate Development Plan" to help farmers switch from growing
plants used in drugs to other crops. The Clinton administration
said it would contribute 1 million dollars to this program.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. contribution to Colombia's anti-drugs efforts have
been condemned in many quarters. Earlier this year, Colombian
Justice Minister Carlos Medellin Becerra said U.S. assistance was
just "small change."
</P>
<P>
The money it provided was just enough to pay for fuel for the
planes and the helicopters used by anti-narcotics police to spray
illegal crops with herbicides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
