<HEADLINE> Intergrated Campaign to Control Soil Erosion in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Erosion control efforts will be
expanded in the Loess Plateau, one of the most eroded areas in the
world, over the next five years, the "China Daily" said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to preserve and reclaim arable land will extend
into more counties in Shanxi, Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous region, which are located in west and
north China.
</P>
<P>
The programme will be organized by county authorities to
achieve wholesale improvement of barren land, said Huang Ziqiang,
deputy director of the Yellow River Conservancy Commission. The
commission is under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of Water
Resources.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the counties account for 15 percent of the area
classified as seriously eroded. The effort will demonstrate that
huge social and economic changes can be brought by integrating
erosion control with other measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 square kilometers of eroded land are expected to be
brought back into use. This would help speed erosion-control
measures along the Yellow River water system, where 60,000 square
kilometers of eroded land are scheduled to be treated in the
1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
Pilot projects have been carried out in Changwu County, in
western Shaanxi Province, and neighbouring Jingchuan County in
Gansu Province since the early 1990s. The large-scale water and
soil conservation drive has paid off, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
In the last five years, the county government has mobilized
thousands of farmers who revived hundreds of thousands of barren
gullies and hills within different small water river systems by
planting grass, trees and crops and building dams and terraced
farmland.
</P>
<P>
This year, Changwu has prevented 460 square kilometers, 84
percent of its eroded areas, from further soil erosion. The annual
amount of sand and soil washed into rivers in Changwu has been
reduced from 1.35 million tons to 900,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the county's gross value of annual
agricultural output increased by 1.8 times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
