<HEADLINE> Romania's NATO Membership Undecided: NATO Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A visiting senior NATO
military officer today refused to comment on the timetable for
Romania's entry into the western alliance, the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The decision on when Romania will be admitted to NATO is a
political one, which shall be made by the 16 member states of the
alliance with Romania, said George Joulwan, NATO's Supreme
Commander of the Allied Powers in Europe, who is on a two-day
visit to Romania on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Joulwan held talks with Romanian President Ion Iliescu and
Romania's military officers during the visit.
</P>
<P>
General Joulwan spoke highly of the changes of the Romanian
military in the past two years and its role in the peace keeping
operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia's opposition against NATO's eastward expansion
can not be changed overnight, Joulwan said.
</P>
<P>
Twelve central and east European nations from the Baltic to
Mediterranean seas, including Romania, have demanded NATO
membership since 1990.
</P>
<P>
But NATO has kept them waiting because of Russia's strong
opposition. Russia insists that the enlargement process will
threaten its national security.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO's eastward expansion process is continuing.
Dialogues with possible candidates for membership have taken place
in the first half of this year, following a visit by NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana to central and eastern Europe
during April and May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
