<HEADLINE> Romania Hails Lifting of Sanctions Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAEST, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Romania today welcomed the
U.N.'s decision to dismantle its four-year economic sanctions
against Yugoslavia, saying the move will help economic cooperation
in the Baltic region and between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Romanian president Ion Iliescu said Romania
also supports Yugoslavia's re-entry into international and
regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council agreed on Tuesday to lift its
economic sanctions against the former Yugoslavia, now made up of
Serbia and Montenegro, following the general election in Bosnia on
September 14.
</P>
<P>
The security council imposed comprehensive sanctions against
Yugoslavia on May 30, 1992, accusing it of supporting Bosnian
Serbs in the Bosnian civil war.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions had led to a big fall in trade volume between
Romania and Yugoslavia. Bilateral trade was below 100 million
U.S. dollars in the first eight months, according to the Romania
Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
With the sanctions lifted, the two nations will work hard to
increase their trade volume to five hundred million U.S. dollars
in the coming four months the agency said, quoting an official of
the Romanian Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Freight volume in the Danube river and Danube-Black Sea canal
is expected to jump as trade gets back to normal, said the
Romanian Transport Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
