<HEADLINE> Swedish Police to Follow Palme Case to S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Swedish police will go to
South Africa within the next week to question those allegedly
involved in the assassination of the then Prime Minister Olof
Palme in 1986, judicial officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Chief prosecutor Jan Danielsson will meet former head of the
South African secret police Eugene de Kock, his predecessor Dirk
Coetzee and "superspy" Craig Williamson after de Kock revealed
last week that South African apartheid secret agents had been
involved in the killing.
</P>
<P>
De Kock and Coetzee are both former policemen convicted of
carrying out murders under the apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
Coetzee also alleged that the murder of Palme, who was a
leading opponent of apartheid, was orchestrated by two other South
African agents, "superspy" Williamson and ex-Rhodesian soldier
Anthony White, who, he claimed, pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
White denied the allegation Monday from his home in
Mozambique. Williamson has also denied any involvement in the
killing.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish foreign ministry has asked South Africa's justice
department for help and expects a response in two or three days.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said today that the
matter should be thoroughly investigated and justice be done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
