<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth of Thai Exports to US slower than Thai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Relative lower competitiveness
of Thai goods has led to a slow growth in their market share in
the United States, according to a Thai Commerce Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of this year, the growth rate for
Thai exports to the U.S. was less than five percent over the same
period last year, as compared to Singapore, Malaysia and the
Philippines which registered a growth of about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed that Thailand's export capability has
declined significantly compared with that of its main ASEAN
rivals.
</P>
<P>
The declines indicated that the U.S. is now able to import from
countries and regions where labor and production costs are lower.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has imported more food products, including fish, meat
and processed foods, and garments, gems and jewelry, footwear and
leather products, from low-cost countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The United States, as the world's largest importer, is growing
by 10.9 percent annually in its imports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand accounted for 1.5 percent of all imports of the U.S.
in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
