<HEADLINE> Indonesia, U.S. May Renegotiate f-16 Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia may renegotiate a
stalled deal to purchase nine f-16 fighter jets from the United
States next January, Antara news agency today quoted a
high-ranking officer as saying.
</P>
<P>
"From what I have learnt from the defense attach at the US
embassy here, there is no problem with the planned sale,"
Indonesian Air Force Chief-of-Staff Vice Marshal Sutria Tubagus
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tubagus said Indonesia's choice of fighter plane to strengthen
its air force under its current five-year development plan (ending
in 1999) was still the f-16.
</P>
<P>
The US had for several times postponed a plan to sell the f-16s
to Indonesia due to the US Congress' objections to how Indonesia
was handling certain domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
Several US senators had feared that Indonesia would use the
planes in dealing with internal security problems, Tubagus said.
 
