<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Champions Cup to Expand by Eight Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The European soccers' governing
body UEFA decided on Thursday that the Champions Cup will be
expanded from current 16 to 24 teams starting from the 1997-98
season.
</P>
<P>
Under the new format, eight strongest soccer powers in the
continent will have their leagues' runners-up to compete in the
qualifiers for the continental tournament.
</P>
<P>
Together with the defending champion, winners of Europe's seven
strongest leagues win automatic berths into the 24-team final.
</P>
<P>
And the qualifiers will decide the other 16 teams from all the
other domestic champions and the second-placer of Europe's top
eight leagues.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the eight top-ranked leagues are Italy, France,
Spain, Germany, Portugal, the Netherlands, England and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The finals will be divided into six groups of four teams, with
the group winners and two best runner-up teams advancing to the
quarterfinal round.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UEFA was interested in hosting a tournament in
December 1997 between the four continental champions from Europe,
Asia, the Americas and Africa.
</P>
<P>
An under-17 tournament from January 29 to February 10, 1997 was
also approved by the UEFA in Portugal between Africa and Europe's
top national youth teams.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoirem and Guinea will represent Africa
while Europe features Spain, France, Portugal and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-Shenzhen Marathon Set for Next February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The rotten wheel of the Hong
Kong-Shenzhen International Marathon Race, greased as the annual
event, has finally found a sponsorship, not for one year, but for
three.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Amateur Athletic Association announced here on
Thursday that it has signed a three-year agreement with Standard
Chartered Bank to sponsor the cross-border sporting event, which
for next year will be held on February 16.
</P>
<P>
This is only the third time the event has been organized since
1992. The race came to a halt after the organizers failed to find
a suitable sponsorship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Chartered Marathon Hong Kong-Shenzhen is expected
to attract some 1,000 runners from Canada, Britain, New Zealand,
the United States, China, South Korea, Japan, Hong Kong and other
Asian-Pacific nations and regions.
</P>
<P>
"This time it is run just before the handover of sovereignty of
Hong Kong to China, which gives this event a very special
meaning," said William Ko, HKAAA's president.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to establish the event as Asia's premier
athletic event, along with the line of such as world-class London
and Boston Marathons," said Ian Wilson, Standard Chartered's
General Manager for Hong Kong, China and Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We considered the marathon an important event and will
mobilize our best efforts and resources to make it a bigger
success than ever before," said Tom Owen, president of the
Shenzhen Track and Field Association.
</P>
<P>
Two races will be held for the 1997 event -- the full-length
marathon of 42.195 kilometers and a half-marathon, 21.098.
</P>
<P>
The participants will run some 10 kilometers in Hong Kong
before crossing into Shenzhen through the Huanggang check
point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
