<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: NZ National Party Focuses Attack on Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 4 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's ruling National
Party is seeking ways to focus attack on the Labor Party, its
leader Helen Clark in particular, in the current election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The selection of Clark as the target is out of the perception
that the Labor leader poses the main threat to Prime Minister Jim
Bolger's effort to retain the prime ministership after the
election, although the Labor's popularity is much lower than the
National.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Bill Birch led the attack Thursday by devoting
much of a speech to criticizing Clark.
</P>
<P>
"The greatest con job of the campaign has been the woeful claim
by Helen Clark that she's shaping up strongly now to be the next
prime minister."
</P>
<P>
"She is begging on television for previously sworn opponents to
fulfill her prime ministerial ambition," Birch was quoted by "The
Dominion" newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new tactic came after the failure of what the opposition
parties described as a scare campaign launched by Bolger to
distance voters from the policies of the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
In the drive, Bolger warned that if the three left-wing
parties, the Labor, Alliance and New Zealand First form a
government after the election, New Zealand will be dragged into
higher taxes, higher unemployment, massive new overseas debt,
declining foreign investments and rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
But the warning has failed to work its way with the NZ dollar,
interest rates and the sharemarket all steady. Foreign investors
have been buying heavily into NZ government bonds.
</P>
<P>
The international rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's has indicated
that it sees no risk to NZ's credit rating if there would be a
change of government.
</P>
<P>
It says a new government is unlikely to depart drastically from
the current policies although the economic reform could slow down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, attacks against each other intensified among the
parties with the election race entering its final stage.
</P>
<P>
In her campaign tour yesterday, Clark still concentrated her
attack on the National in social areas, accusing the National of
trying to hide the 'social scandal" of poverty. She pledged to set
up a commission to fight poverty.
</P>
<P>
Alliance leader Jim Anderton has termed as cynical the
rapprochement yesterday between Helen Clark and former Labor
leader Mike Moore, who once opposed Clark's leadership. He
predicted Moore will take another tilt at the leadership if the
Labor does not perform well in the election.
</P>
<P>
He also charged NZ First leader Winston Peters of preparing the
ground for a post-election deal with the National, asserting that
Peters would be looking for senior cabinet positions for NZ First
MPs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
