<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Muslims Agree to Leave Serb Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the NATO-led
peace Implementation Force (IFOR) and Bosnian Muslims reached an
agreement today that all Muslims who entered the Serb village of
Jusici illegally should pull out.
</P>
<P>
IFOR spokesman Simon Haselock told reporters in Sarajevo that
the Muslim refugees would leave behind in the village three
representatives to liaise with the IFOR and that 10 others would
be authorized to make daily inspections, according to the Tanjug
news agency.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 300 Muslim refugees who entered into the Serb town
of Jusici near Zvornik in eastern Bosnia on September 20 and 21
had moved out three days before. They said they were repairing
their old houses in Jusici but the IFOR had found and confiscated
weapons from some of these Muslims.
</P>
<P>
About 60 hard-line Muslims have remained, however, threatening
to go on hunger strike and arguing that once they left, they would
not be allowed to return to the village again.
</P>
<P>
IFOR sources said to the effect that the refugees were
guaranteed the right to return under the agreement, which is based
on a proposal by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
It gives the Muslims 72 hours to evacuate the village in order
to allow the UNHCR to prepare everything for their legal return.
</P>
<P>
The IFOR has branded the entry by the Muslims as illegal,
saying many of them had arms with them in an attempt to make
provocation in the Serb land.
</P>
<P>
Under the UNHCR's plan, the Muslims should apply to Republika
Srpska's authorities for permission to settle and submit documents
to prove that they had actually had property in Jusici before the
war broke out in early 1992.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in Republika Srpska insist that returning Muslims
and Croats should sign statements undertaking to abide by the laws
of Republika Srpska. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediterranean Environment Office Set Up in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of Egypt and
some international institutions have agreed to set up the region's
first environmental office in Cairo, the World Bank announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
A Memorandum of Understanding establishing the Mediterranean
Environmental Technical Assistance Program (METAP) Regional
Facility in Cairo was signed here by Egyptian Minister of Public
Enterprise Sector and Minister of State for Administrative
Development and Environment Atef Ebeid, European Investment Bank
(EIB) Vice President Ariane Obolensky and World Bank Vice
President for the Middle East and North Africa Kemal Dervis on
behalf of Egypt and the METAP donors.
</P>
<P>
The METAP partners, including the European Commission, EIB, the
United Nations Development Program and the World Bank have agreed
to set up the facility in a bid to bring together Mediterranean
countries to identity environmental projects, strengthen
environmental capacities and help promote action and effective
policy measures.
</P>
<P>
The facility's main functions will be to prepare investment
projects to help arrest and prevent pollution and to support water
resources management efforts throughout the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
