<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF Conclude 1996 Annual Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank concluded their joint 1996 annual
meetings here today, and about 46 governors representing nearly
all countries of the world addressed the three-day plenary
session.
</P>
<P>
In his concluding remarks at a brief closing ceremony, Michel
Camdessus, chairman of the Executive Board and managing director
of the IMF, called upon the world's financial officials to join
their efforts to strive for the common goals: "greater stability
in the world, and stronger, more sustained, more broadly shared
and higher quality growth."
</P>
<P>
Both World Bank President James Wolfensohn and IMF chief Michel
Camdessus raised louder alarm against corruption during the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference, Wolfensohn vowed to pull out of any
project funded by his institution that proved to be tainted by
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"Where there are projects to which we are involved and we find
evidence of corruption we will cancel the project," he told
reporters. "We are anxious to put teeth into what we're doing over
issues in which we have control."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank chief said graft and other practices are a major
barrier to economic progress in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Wolfensohn added, corruption may threaten to rob the
World Bank of financial backing in industrial countries as
governments -- and the voters who elect them -- wonder if the
money they have provided is ending up in the pockets of corrupt
officials.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also took aim at these practices during a speech
to the plenary session, saying governments must demonstrate that
they have no tolerance for corruption in any form.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank board recently set up new procurement guidelines
for projects financed by its loans. Under the guidelines, the
World Bank can cancel part of a loan if it finds out that corrupt
or fraudulent practices are involved in procurement contracts. It
can also bar guilty companies from bidding on future bank-financed
projects.
</P>
<P>
During his concluding press conference, Wolfensohn noted that
what World Bank can do is to pull out its resources from projects
and that the bank could not become a moral policeman or interfere
in the political policies of countries. Nor, he added, will such
efforts change human behavior overnight.
</P>
<P>
"The bank will not interfere in the political sphere..., but we
can try to create a climate in which people fight corruption,"
Wolfensohn stressed.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn made clear he is not playing any favorites. He noted
that corruption is a worldwide problem in which wealthy industrial
countries, in their efforts to do business in the developing
world, have added to the climate of loose practices.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the strong anti-corruption tune, Camdessus
told reporters today that the outgoing annual meetings have four
predominant features: the expression by governors of all countries
of their optimistic views over their economic performances and
outlook; a strong sense of implementation of common strategies;
the demand for a strong and effective IMF; and an increasing sense
of partnership between the donors and recipients, between
developed and developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
