<HEADLINE> Nigeria Calls for Fair World Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today called for
the establishment of a fair world order so that enduring peace can
be founded.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the general debate at the current U.N. General
Assembly session, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said that
peace and development are mutually reinforcing. A just and
enduring peace can only be founded on the general socio-economic
progress of all nations, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it is disconcerting to see that while the
countries of the North are becoming more affluent, the countries
of the South which constitute the majority of the world population
are getting more impoverished.
</P>
<P>
Deepening crisis of development in the poor countries "can
undermine a new world order which we seek to create," he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to have close cooperation
with Africa which is suffering from heavy external debt and
deteriorating terms of trade. It should also help to carry out the
promises under the new United Nations New Agenda for the
Development of Africa in the 1990s, he said.
</P>
<P>
In this connection, he observed, the United Nations has a
central role to play in boosting the global economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
