<HEADLINE> Mandela on S. Africa's Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today that nobody has the right to dictate to
his government on which countries it should have relations with.
</P>
<P>
"No country can dictate to me what to do about relations with
any country," Mandela told a press conference after meeting a
delegation from the South African Jewish Board of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the fact that he had been advised by
"certain western countries" to end its relations with Iran, Libya
and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"The advice is coming from western countries," he said without
naming them.
</P>
<P>
"They are the people now saying we should ignore the people
who helped us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Mandela brushed aside the displeasure of
the United States government over his decision to host Iranian
President Ali Akbar Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had also invited leaders of Libya and Cuba to visit
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
