<HEADLINE> Christopher Says No Loser at Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher said today that both the Palestinians and the
Israelis came out winners in the Wednesday-concluded summit
meeting because they recommitted themselves to a peaceful future.
</P>
<P>
"I think the conversation that took place, the recommitment to
a non-violent future, the commitment to have intensive, indeed
continuous negotiation is a step forward," Christopher said during
a picture session with Tunisian Foreign Minister Habib Ban Yahia.
"In that sense everyone comes out a winner," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian officials described the two-day summit of
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat as fruitless.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians said that the Israeli side neither gave a date
for the pulling back of Israeli troops in the West Bank town of
Hebron nor agreed to close the newly opened entrance to a viewing
tunnel near the Temple Mount in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1993 interim settlement between the two sides, the
redeployment was supposed to be carried out five months ago. The
opening of the entrance triggered a bloody violence in the
region, leaving more than 70 people dead.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said Wednesday in wrapping up the
U.S.-sponsored summit meeting, "We have not made as much progress
as I wish we had." But he also said, "We are in better shape than
we were two days ago."
</P>
<P>
Anyhow, the two sides agreed to continue their peace process by
starting their negotiations Sunday at Erez, a border crossing
between Israel and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced Wednesday Dennis Ross as U.S. mediator in the
talks. Christopher acknowledged that there were difficult times
ahead and he was ready to offer help in the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
