<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issue of Elderly Catches UN Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
seeking answers as to how the rights and security of older persons
can be guaranteed with the aging of the world population.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. projection, the world's older population
aged 60 and above will grow from half a billion people in 1990 to
almost 1.5 billion people in 2050. They will mainly be in
developing countries, particularly in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"That demographic transition has skyrocketed the proportion of
older persons within a few generations from about one person in
14, to one in four," according to a U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is often the cause of isolation, ill health and even
premature death," said U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali in his message for the International Day for Older
Persons on October 1, which was designated by the U.N. General
Assembly in 1990 in response to the call for the caring of the old
generation.
</P>
<P>
The situation of older women has caught the particular concern
of the world community, according to researchers. Worldwide, women
are living longer than men. But women are more likely to be poorer
in old age than men for various reasons, which include involvement
in home-making and child-bearing, interruption of careers because
of family responsibilities, less investment in training and
education, and labor force discrimination and lower paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
Due to the gradual losses of their ability to work, old people
tend to suffer most economically, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
During a conference called "Challenges to older peoples'
economic security around the world" here today, researchers and
experts agreed that the improvement of the social insurance
systems is to help overcome economic difficulties of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
However, privatization of the social security system advocated
in some countries has created many new problems. Some people in
the United States want to turn the entire social security fund
over to the Wall Street investment companies to run for profit.
</P>
<P>
The ideologues and the profit-seekers have greatly exaggerated
the easily-fixed financial problems facing Social Security, Fred
Solowey, an American researcher and writer, said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Countries of the Organization of Economic Cooperation and
Development, which include mainly the United States, Canada and
major European countries, face a no easy task for securing the
economic conditions of the elderly. It is expected that by 2030
the proportion of these countries will reach a ratio of one person
in three.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the conference, some were at their 80s,
expected that institutional mechanisms will be found out to ensure
that older persons in all societies have economic and social
security that they need. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961004.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Federal Government to Support Charter Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Education Department
today announced nearly-17-million-dollar federal grants to help
set up hundreds of charter schools that are not bound by
conventional rules in 19 states, Puerto Rico and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
The grants were in the budget for fiscal 1996, which ended
Monday, and the amount was a marked increase over the 6 million
dollars spent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Charter schools, set up by groups of parents, teachers, school
administrators and others, operate without many of the constraints
imposed by local public school districts. A charter outlines what
students are expected to learn, but this can be revoked if the
school fails to meet the goals.
</P>
<P>
Since the first charter school opened in Minnesota in 1992, 24
other states and the District of Columbia have started the
program. At the end of 1995, 269 charter schools were serving
60,000 students. An additional 70 schools were scheduled to open
this fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
