<HEADLINE> Tunisia Arrests Assassins of Former Belgian Vice Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian police arrested early
this week two assassins of former Belgian Vice Prime Minister
Andre Cools, who was killed on July 18, 1991 near Liege, eastern
Belgium, in a parking lot outside the residence of his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
Tunisian Minister of Justice Sadol Sha'abane said today that
Abdelmajid Almi, 24, and Abdeljelil Ben Brahim, 31, two Tunisian
nationals who had long lived in Europe, admitted that they killed
Cools under a contract signed with a European, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse (AFP) said that the arrest of the two men
will allow the relaunching of an inquiry into the assassination
whose vicissitude has kept Belgium in suspense for five years.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that piece by piece, the puzzle is taking shape one
month after the arrest of the former Belgian minister Alain Van
der Biest, who was accused of masterminding the assassination, and
five of his associates.
</P>
<P>
Domenico Castellino, an Italian-Belgian who was close to Van
der Biest, admitted after being arrested early last month that he
had recruited Almi and Ben Brahim in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
Belgium will reportedly send a judicial team to Tunisia next
week to question the two men, who are now jailed in the central
prison of Tunis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
